Unlike oligodendrocyte precursor cell, it does not initially express PDGFR-alpha and can differentiate into both type-1 and type-2 astrocytes.
A thymocyte that has the phenotype CD4-negative, CD8-negative, CD44-negative, CD25-negative, and pre-TCR-positive.
A thymocyte that has the phenotype CD4-negative, CD8-negative, CD44-negative, and CD25-positive and expressing the T cell receptor beta-chain in complex with the pre-T cell receptor alpha chain.
A thymocyte that has the phenotype CD4-negative, CD8-negative, CD44-positive, and CD25-positive.
A thymocyte that has the phenotype CD4-negative, CD8-positive, CD44-negative, CD25-negative, and pre-TCR-positive.
A thymocyte expressing the alpha-beta T cell receptor complex as well as both the CD4 and CD8 coreceptors.
A gamma-delta T cell that has a mature phenotype. These cells can be found in tissues and circulation where they express unique TCR repertoire depending on their location.

term: CD4-negative CD8-negative gamma-delta intraepithelial T cell
comment: A gamma-delta intraepithelial T cell that has the phenotype CD4-negative and CD8-negative.

term: CD8-alpha alpha positive, gamma-delta intraepithelial T cell
comment: A gamma-delta intraepithelial T cell that has the phenotype CD8-alpha alpha-positive.
A mature gamma-delta T cell that is found in the columnar epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract. These cells participate in mucosal immune responses.
Any renal cortical epithelial cell that is part of some renal corpuscle.
Any kidney medulla cell that is part of some outer medulla of kidney.
Any kidney tubule cell that is part of some renal cortex tubule.
Any kidney cortical cell that is part of some juxtaglomerular apparatus.
Any kidney medulla cell that is part of some inner medulla of kidney.

A B cell of distinct lineage and surface marker expression. B-1 B cells are thought to be the primary source of natural IgM immunoglobulin, that is, IgM produced in large quantities without prior antigenic stimulation and generally reactive against various microorganisms, as well as the source of T-independent IgA immunoglobulin in the mucosal areas. These cells are CD43-positive.

An immature B cell of an intermediate stage between the pre-B cell stage and the mature naive stage with the phenotype surface IgM-positive and CD19-positive, and are subject to the process of B cell selection. A transitional B cell migrates from the bone marrow into the peripheral circulation, and then to the spleen.
A precursor B cell is a B cell with the phenotype CD10-positive.

An immature B cell is a B cell that has the phenotype surface IgM-positive and surface IgD-negative, and have not undergone class immunoglobulin class switching or peripheral encounter with antigen and activation.
An immature alpha-beta T cell that is located in the thymus and is CD8-positive and CD4-negative.
An immature alpha-beta T cell that is located in the thymus and is CD4-positive and CD8-negative.
A T cell which regulates overall immune responses as well as the responses of other T cell subsets through direct cell-cell contact and cytokine release.

A mature alpha-beta T cell of a distinct lineage that bears natural killer markers and a T cell receptor specific for a limited set of ligands. NK T cells have activation and regulatory roles particularly early in an immune response.
A long-lived, antigen-experienced T cell that has acquired a memory phenotype including distinct surface markers and the ability to differentiate into an effector T cell upon antigen reexposure.
Any cell that is part of some ureter.
Any cell that is part of some lower urinary tract.
Any neuron that has its soma located in some kidney.
A myeloblast committed to the basophil lineage.
A progenitor cell of the thrombocyte, a nucleated blood cell involved in coagulation typically seen in birds and other non-mammalian vertebrates.
A lymphoid progenitor cell of the T cell lineage, with some lineage specific marker expression, but not yet fully committed to the T cell lineage.
A conventional B cell subject to antigenic stimulation and dependent on T cell help and with a distinct surface marker expression pattern from B-1 B cells. These cells are CD43-negative.
A B-1 B cell that has the phenotype CD5-negative, but having other phenotypic attributes of a B-1 B cell.
A B-1 B cell that has the phenotype CD5-positive.

A progenitor cell of the B cell lineage, with some lineage specific activity such as early stages of recombination of B cell receptor genes, but not yet fully committed to the B cell lineage until the expression of PAX5 occurs.

A lymphoid progenitor cell that is committed to the natural killer cell lineage, expressing CD122 (IL-15) receptor, but lacking many of the phenotypic characteristics of later stages of natural killer cell development such as expression of NK activating and inhibitory molecules. In human this cell has the phenotype CD34-positive, CD45RA-positive, CD10-positive, CD117-negative, and CD161 negative.
A natural killer cell that is developmentally mature and expresses a variety of inhibitory and activating receptors that recognize MHC class I and other stress related molecules.
A natural killer cell that is developmentally immature and expresses natural killer cell receptors (NKR).
A progenitor cell restricted to the myeloid lineage.
A progenitor cell restricted to the lymphoid lineage.
A promyelocyte committed to the eosinophil lineage.
A myeloblast committed to the eosinophil lineage.
A progenitor cell of the mast cell lineage. Markers for this cell are FceRIa-low, CD117-positive, CD9-positive, T1/ST2-positive, SCA1-negative, and lineage-negative.
A promyelocyte committed to the basophil lineage.

A hematopoietic multipotent progenitor cell is multipotent, but not capable of long-term self-renewal. These cells are characterized as lacking lineage cell surface markers and being CD34-positive in both mice and humans.

A precursor in the granulocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between a myeloblast and myelocyte, that has distinct nucleoli, a nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio of 5:1 to 3:1, and containing a few primary cytoplasmic granules. Markers for this cell are fucosyltransferase FUT4-positive, CD33-positive, integrin alpha-M-negative, low affinity immunoglobulin gamma Fc region receptor III-negative, and CD24-negative.

The most primitive precursor in the granulocytic series, having fine, evenly distributed chromatin, several nucleoli, a high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ration (5:1-7:1), and a nongranular basophilic cytoplasm. They reside in the bone marrow.
A progenitor cell of the neutrophil lineage.

An immature cell of the conventional dendritic cell lineage, characterized by high levels of antigen uptake via endocytosis, macropinocytosis, and phagocytosis, and typically found resident in the tissues. Markers for this cell are CD80-low, CD86-low, and MHC-II-low.
An olfactory receptor cell with short cilia growing in an invagination bordered by microvilli.

A rapidly cycling mature B cell that has distinct phenotypic characteristics and is involved in T-dependent immune responses and located typically in the germinal centers of lymph nodes. This cell type expresses Ly77 after activation.

A resting mature B cell that has the phenotype IgM-positive, IgD-positive, CD23-positive and CD21-positive, and found in the B cell follicles of the white pulp of the spleen or the corticol areas of the peripheral lymph nodes. This cell type is also described as being CD19-positive, B220-positive, AA4-negative, CD43-negative, and CD5-negative.
A leukocyte with a single non-segmented nucleus in the mature form.
A mature cell of the conventional dendritic cell lineage, characterized by a high capacity for antigen presentation and typically found in a lymph node.
An olfactory receptor cell in which the apical ending of the dendrite is a knob that bears numerous microvilli.
An olfactory receptor cell in which the apical ending of the dendrite is a pronounced ciliated olfactory knob.
Any epithelial cell that is part of some mesonephric nephron tubule.
An epithelial cell of the vestibular sensory organ that is characterized by intense enzymatic activities and numerous basal membrane infoldings.

term: marginal zone B cell of spleen
comment: A mature B cell that is located in the marginal zone of the spleen with the phenotype CD23-negative and CD21-positive and expressing a B cell receptor usually reactive to bacterial cell wall components or senescent self components such as oxidized-LDL. This cell type is also described as being CD19-positive, B220-positive, IgM-high, AA4-negative, CD35-high.
Notochordal cell that is inner portion of the notochord and becomes vacuolated as development proceeds.
Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into a chondroblast. and arises from neural crest, meseosdermal and notochordal and connective tissue cells.

Neuromast mantle cell is a non-sensory cell. Neuromast mantle cells surround the neuromast support cells and neuromast hair cells, separating the neuromast from the epidermis, and secrete cupula in which the ciliary bundles of all the hair cells are embedded.
Mesodermal cell that is axially located and gives rise to the cells of the notochord.
A neuron that releases serotonin as a neurotransmitter.
Notochordal cell that is part of the outer epithelium of the notochord and surrounds the vacuolated notochord cells.
Cell that is part of the neural crest region of the neuroepithelium, prior to migration. Note that not all premigratory neural crest cells may become migratory neural crest cells.
Cell that is part of the notochord.
Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into a cementoblast.
Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to form an odontoblast, deposits predentine, and arises from a cranial neural crest cell.

Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into an ameloblast. Located in the inner enamel epithelium, these cells elongate, their nuclei shift distally (away from the dental papilla), and their cytoplasm becomes filled with organelles needed for synthesis and secretion of enamel proteins.
Cell that has the potential to form a skeletal cell type (e.g. cells in periosteum, cells in marrow) and produce extracellular matrix (often mineralized) and skeletal tissue (often mineralized).
A mesothelial cell that is part of the peritoneum.
Hair cell is a mechanoreceptor cell that is sensitive to movement of the hair-like projections (stereocilia and kinocilia) which relay the information centrally in the nervous system.
A mesothelial cell that is part of the parietal pleura.
Interneuromast cell is a neuroectodermal cell deposited by the migrating lateral line primordium between the neuromasts. Interneuromast cells proliferate and migrate to form additional neuromasts.
A mesothelial cell that is part of the pleura.

Olfactory epithelial support cell is a columnar cell that extends from the epithelial free margin to the basement membrane of the olfactory epithelium. This cell type has a large, vertically, elongate, euchromatic nucleus, along with other nuclei, forms a layer superficial to the cell body of the receptor cell. sends long somewhat irregular microvilli into the mucus layer. at the base, with expanded end-feet containing numerous lamellated dense bodies resembling lipofuscin of neurons.
An epithelial cell that is part of a nephron tubule.

Neuromast support cell is a non-sensory cell of the neuromast that extend between the sensory hair cells from the basement membrane to the apical surface. neuromast support cells are surrounded by neuromast mantle cells.
A mesothelial cell that is part of the visceral pleura.
A skeletal muscle myoblast that differentiates into fast muscle fibers.
A goblet cell that is part of the small intestine.
A skeletal muscle myoblast that differentiates into slow muscle fibers.

Neuromast hair cell is a hair cell that acts as a sensory receptor of the neuromast. it is morphologically polarized as a result of the relative position of the single kinocilium and the clusters of stereocilia on its apical surface.
A cell that is part of a kidney.
A reticular cell that is part of the splenic cord.

An epithelial cell that is part of the bile duct. Cholangiocytes contribute to bile secretion via net release of bicarbonate and water. They are cuboidal epithelium in the small interlobular bile ducts, but become columnar and mucus secreting in larger bile ducts approaching the porta hepatis and the extrahepatic ducts.
A macrophage that suppresses immune responses.
An epidermal cell with apical microvilli or a single apical projection have synaptic associations with nerve fibres in the epidermis.

A macrophage which develops from an inflammatory monocyte and is recruited into the tissues in response to injury and infection as part of an inflammatory response. Markers include CD11b-positive, CD68-positive, and F4/80-positive.
Ciliated cell of the embryonic epidermis and functions in embryonic movements.

A monocyte that responds rapidly to microbial stimuli by secreting cytokines and antimicrobial factors and which is characterized by high expression of CCR2 in both rodents and humans, negative for the lineage markers CD3, CD19, and CD20, and of larger size than non-classical monocytes.
Muscle precursor cell that is adjacent to the notochord and part of the presomitic mesoderm.
Odontoblast that is terminally differentiated and derived from an odontogenic papilla and associated with dentine.
Neuron that is part of the enteric nervous system.
Odontoblast that non-terminally differentiated, located in the odontogenic papilla and dentine tissue, and transforms from a odontoblast cell.
Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to transform into an osteoblast, and develops from neural crest or mesodermal cells.
A tissue-resident macrophage resident found in the thymus, involved in the clearance of apoptotic thymocytes.
Any chondrocyte that is part of the tracheobronchial tree.
A transitional myocyte that is part of the atrioventricular bundle.
A gut-associated lymphoid tissue macrophage found in lamina propria of the gut.
Any serous secreting cell that is part of the tracheobronchial epithelium.
A transitional myocyte that is part of the internodal tract.

A macrophage constitutively resident in a particular tissue under non-inflammatory conditions, and capable of phagocytosing a variety of extracellular particulate material, including immune complexes, microorganisms, and dead cells.
A Purkinje myocyte that is part of the internodal tract.

An elicited macrophage that is recruited into the tissues in response to injury and infection as part of an inflammatory response, expresses high levels of pro-inflammatory cytokines, ROS and NO, and shows potent microbicidal activity.
Any goblet cell that is part of the tracheobronchial epithelium.

term: myocardial endocrine cell of interventricular septum
comment: A myocardial endocrine cell that is part of the interventricular septum.
Any neuron that has its soma located in some retrotrapezoid nucleus.
A gut-associated lymphoid tissue macrophage found in tonsils.
A Purkinje myocyte that is part of the atrioventricular bundle.
A secondary lymphoid organ macrophage found in a lymph node. This cell is CD169-high.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the prostate gland.
A tissue-resident macrophage found in a secondary lymphoid organ.

A basal cell that is part of the urothelium. Compared to other urothelial cell types, a basal cell of the urothelium is positioned along the basement membrane, is the most undifferentiated and serves a progenitor role.
A transitional myocyte that is part of the sinoatrial node.

term: cardiac pacemaker cell of sinoatrial node
comment: A nodal myocyte that is part of the sinoatrial node.
A Purkinje myocyte that is part of the atrioventricular node.
A splenic macrophage found in the areas surrounding the white pulp of the spleen, adjacent to the marginal sinus. Markers include F4/80-negative, Dectin2-low, sialoadhesin-positive.

A splenic macrophage found in the marginal zone of the spleen, involved in recognition and clearance of particulate material from the splenic circulation. Markers include F4/80-negative, MARCO-positive, SR-A-positive, SIGN-R1-positive, and Dectin2-positive.
A secondary lymphoid organ macrophage found in the spleen.
A gut-associated lymphoid tissue macrophage found in the Peyer's patches.

A specialized pore forming cell of the follicle, located adjacent to the animal pole of the oocyte. The micropylar cell makes the single micropyle (pore) through the chorion through which the sperm fertilizes the egg.
Epidermal cell rich in mitochondria. In amphibians, appears during metamorphosis.
Characteristic early embryonic cell with a bottle or flask shape that is first to migrate inwards at the blastopore during gastrulation in amphibians.

Secretory cell that produces a chemical mixture that triggers antipredator behavior. The substance is released only upon disruption of the epidermis. [Behavior of teleost fishes, second edition, edited by Pitcher, 1992]
A smooth muscle cell that is part of any lymphatic vessel.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the tracheobronchial tree.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of any blood vessel.

A splenic white pulp macrophage found in and around the germinal centers of the white pulp of the spleen that participates in phagocytosis of apoptotic B cells from the germinal centers. A marker for a cell of this type is Mertk-positive.

term: myoepithelial cell of primary lactiferous duct
comment: A myoepithelial cell that is part of the primary lactiferous duct.
A splenic macrophage found in the white pulp of the spleen. Markers include F4/80-negative, CD68-positive, and macrosialin-positive.

A type of monocyte characterized by low expression of CCR2, low responsiveness to monocyte chemoattractant CCL2/MCP1, low phagocytic activity, and decrease size relative to classical monocytes, but increased co-stimulatory activity. May also play a role in tissue repair.

An eosinophil with a ring-shaped nucleus that is resident in the lung parenchyma. In mouse, lung parenchyma resident eosinophils are IL-5-independent Siglec-F(intermediate) CD62L+ CD101(low). In human, they are Siglec-8+ CD62L+ IL-3R(low).

term: myoepithelial cell of tertiary lactiferous duct
comment: A myoepithelial cell that is part of the tertiary lactiferous duct.

A splenic macrophage found in the red-pulp of the spleen, and involved in immune responses to blood-borne pathogens and in the clearance of senescent erythrocytes. Markers include F4/80-positive, CD68-positive, MR-positive, Dectin2-positive, macrosialin-positive, and sialoadhesin-low.

term: myoepithelial cell of secondary lactiferous duct
comment: A myoepithelial cell that is part of the secondary lactiferous duct.

term: myoepithelial cell of quarternary lactiferous duct
comment: A myoepithelial cell that is part of the quarternary lactiferous duct.
Any cell that is part of some urethra.

A border associated macrophage that is part of a meninx. This macrophage type is elongated and amoeboid spindle-shaped with limited mobility. This macrophage is highly phagocytic, expresses scavenger receptors, has dynamic protrusions and extends its processes during inflammation.
A tissue-resident macrophage found in the central nervous system.

A border associated macrophage found at the interface between the blood and the cerebrospinal fluid in the brain. This central nervous system macrophage has a star-like shaped body and expresses scavenger receptors.
A chromaffin cell that is part of the left ovary.
A chromaffin cell that is part of the right ovary.

term: myoepithelial cell of main lactiferous duct
comment: A myoepithelial cell that is part of the main lactiferous duct.

term: myoepithelial cell of acinus of lactiferous gland
comment: A myoepithelial cell that is part of the acinus of lactiferous gland.
A tissue-resident macrophage found in the mucosa associated lymphoid tissue.
A pericyte cell located in the kidney interstitium.
A thymic macrophage found in the thymic cortex.
A thymic macrophage found in the thymic medulla.

A border associated macrophage that is adjacent to a small blood vessel of a brain. A perivascular macrophage expresses the markers CD14, CD16 and CD163. In homeostatic conditions, this central nervous system macrophage has a non-motile cell body with extending and retracting projections through the blood vessel wall.
Any cell that is part of some urinary bladder.
Any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule midzonal region. These cells have mixed functionality in comparison with those in the other two regions of the liver lobule.
Any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule centrilobular region. These cells are the primary location for the biotransformation of drugs.
A cell that initiates an electrical signal and passes that signal to another cell.
A lymph node macrophage found in the cortex of lymph nodes, in particular in and around the germinal centers, and that participates in phagocytosis of apoptotic B cells from the germinal centers.

A lymph node macrophage found in the subcapsular sinus of lymph nodes that participates in sensing, clearance, and antigen presentation of lymph-borne particulate antigens. This macrophage is capable of activating invaraint NKT cells and is CD169-positive.
An interneuron that has its cell body in a central nervous system.

term: nasal and broncial associated lymphoid tissue macrophage
comment: A mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue macrophage found in the nasal and bronchial mucosa-associated lymphoid tissues.
Any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule periportal region. These cells are primarily involved in oxidative energy metabolism.
A mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue macrophage found in the mucosa-associated lymphoid tissues of the gut.
Any male germ cell that has characteristic some haploid and is capable of some fertilization.

An epithelial cell of the extrahepatic bile ducts, including the left and right hepatic duct, common hepatic duct, and common bile duct. They are columnar in shape, and have a large nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio relative to small/intrahepatic cholangiocytes.
A cell that anchors the cell body of a scolopidial neuron to the integument.

term: endothelial cell of pericentral hepatic sinusoid
comment: An endothelial cell found in the centrilobular region hepatic sinusoid, near the central vein. The fenestrae of these cells are smaller but more numerous compared with those of endothelial cells near the periportal region of the hepatic sinusoid.
A chromaffin cell that is part of the ovary.

An immature myeloid leukocyte of heterogeneous phenotype found particularly in cancer and sepsis patients that is capable of suppressing activity of T cells in ex vivo assays. This cell type is CD45-positive, CD11b-positive.

term: endothelial cell of periportal hepatic sinusoid
comment: An endothelial cell found in the periportal region hepatic sinusoid, near the portal triad. The fenestrae of these cells are larger but fewer in number compared with those of endothelial cells near the centrilobular region of the hepatic sinusoid.
A type of cell containing lipids in small vacuoles and typically seen in atherolosclerotic lesions, as well as other conditions.
A mesothelial cell that is part of the parietal peritoneum.
An elicited macrophage characterized by low production of pro-inflammatory and Th1 polarizing cytokines and high expression of arginase-1, and associated with tissue remodelling.
A melanocyte that is part of the skin of body.
A mesothelial cell that is part of the visceral peritoneum.
An epithelial cell of the hypodermis of Caenorhabditis.

term: naive thymus-derived CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell
comment: An antigen inexperienced CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell with the phenotype CCR7-positive, CD127-positive and CD62L-positive. This cell type develops in the thymus. This cell type is also described as being CD25-negative, CD62L-high, and CD44-low.
A pro-T cell that has the phenotype CD4-negative, CD8-negative, CD44-positive, and CD25-negative.
An immature T cell located in the thymus.

term: smooth muscle cell derived foam cell
comment: A type of foam cell derived from a smooth muscle cell containing lipids in small vacuoles and typically seen in atherolosclerotic lesions, as well as other conditions.
A cell whose nucleus has two haploid genomes.
CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell with the phenotype RORgamma-t-positive, CXCR3-negative, CCR6-positive, and capable of producing IL-17.
Mature T cell not yet exposed to antigen with the phenotype CCR7-positive, CD45RA-positive, and CD127-positive. This cell type is also described as being CD25-negative, CD62L-high and CD44-low.
A cell whose nucleus contains a single haploid genome.
A CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell that has differentiated into a memory T cell.
An epithelial cell that is part of the glomerular capsule.
A cell that contains more than two haploid sets of chromosomes.
A recently activated CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell with the phenotype CD69-positive, CD62L-negative, CD127-negative, and CD25-positive.
An epithelial fate stem cell found in flatworms.

Goblet cells reside throughout the length of the small and large intestine and are responsible for the production and maintenance of the protective mucus blanket by synthesizing and secreting high-molecular-weight glycoproteins known as mucins. Human intestinal goblet cells secrete the MUC2 mucin, as well as a number of typical mucus components: CLCA1, FCGBP, AGR2, ZG16, and TFF3.
An epithelial cell that is part of the glomerular parietal epithelium.

An epithelial cell found in C. elegans that firmly hold the outer body wall and the lips to the inner cylinder of the pharynx in a manner that keeps these organs from breaking apart, while still giving each organ freedom of movement during feeding.
An epithelial cell that is part of the collecting duct of renal tubule.
Any brush cell that is part of the intestinal epithelium.
An epithelial cell that is part of the intermediate tubule.
A myoepithelial cell that is part of the dilatator pupillae.

term: mesothelial cell of anterior chamber of eye
comment: A mesothelial cell that is part of the anterior chamber of eyeball.

term: epithelial cell of stratum germinativum of esophagus
comment: A basal cell that is part of the epithelium of esophagus.
A smooth muscle cell of the trachea.
A cell whose primary function is to cause growth by stimulating cell division in its immediate cellular environment.
An epithelial cell that is part of the nephron.
A free floating cell, including amebocytes and eleocytes, in the coelom of certain animals, especially annelids.
An epithelial cell that is part of the sweat gland.
An epithelial cell that forms a syncytium, which is a multinucleated cell resulting from the fusion of multiple cells.
Any fibroblast of lung that is part of a bronchus.
Any keratinocyte that is part of a hair follicle.
Any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a endometrial blood vessel.

term: dentate gyrus of hippocampal formation stellate cell
comment: Any stellate cell that is part of a dentate gyrus of hippocampal formation.
A transcriptomically distinct astrocyte that is found in the cerebral cortex.
Forms the terminal part of the cuticle-lined excretory duct of C. elegans.
An astrocyte of the spinal cord.
A cell involved in the elimination of metabolic and foreign toxins, and in maintaining the ionic, acid-base and water balance of biological fluids.
A neural crest cell that gives rise to cells of the enteric nervous system.
A neuron with a soma found in the hippocampus.
A smooth muscle cell of the uterus.
An epithelial cell that is part of the viscerocranial mucosa.
Any dopaminergic neuron that is part of a midbrain.
A columnar epithelial cell that is part of an insect imaginal disc.
Any connective tissue cell that is part of some annulus fibrosus disci intervertebralis.

term: fibroblast of the reticular layer of dermis
comment: Any fibroblast that is part of a reticular layer of dermis.
An astrocyte of the cerebellum.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the ciliary body.
Any hematopoietic stem cell that is part of a umbilical cord blood.

term: cycling endothelial cell of lymphatic vessel
comment: A(n) endothelial cell of lymphatic vessel that is cycling.
A scaffolding cell type found in C. elegans, this cell plays a supportive role to the muscle arms. May also have an endocrine role.
An astrocyte that is part of the hippocampus.

term: urothelial cell of trigone of urinary bladder
comment: An urothelial cell that is part of the trigone of urinary bladder.

term: nasal cavity respiratory epithelium epithelial cell of viscerocranial mucosa
comment: Any epithelial cell of viscerocranial mucosa that is part of a nasal cavity respiratory epithelium.
A(n) mononuclear phagocyte that is cycling.

term: epithelial cell of external acoustic meatus
comment: An epithelial cell that is part of the external acoustic meatus.
An epithelial cell that is part of the lacrimal canaliculus.
A neuron of the raphe nuclei.
An epithelial cell that is part of the lacrimal sac.

term: neuron of the dorsal spinal cord
comment: A CNS neuron of the dorsal spinal cord.

term: epithelial cell of lacrimal drainage system
comment: An epithelial cell that is part of the lacrimal drainage system.

term: epithelial cell of wall of inferior part of anal canal
comment: An epithelial cell that is part of the wall of inferior part of anal canal.

A granulosa cell that has a cuboidal morphology and develops from squamous granulosa cell during the transition between primordial follicle to primary follicle. Cuboidal granulosa cells proliferate to form a second layer within secondary follicles.

A fibroblast that synthesizes collagen and uses it to produce reticular fibers, thus providing structural support. Reticular cells are found in many organs, including the spleen, lymph nodes and kidneys. Subtypes of reticular cells include epithelial, mesenchymal, and fibroblastic reticular cells. Fibroblastic reticular cells are involved in directing B cells and T cells to specific regions within a tissue, whereas epithelial and mesenchymal reticular cells are associated with certain areas of the brain.
An epithelial cell that is part of the nasolacrimal duct.

A granulosa cell that has a squamous morphology and form a single layer around the oocyte in primordial follicles. This cell develops directly into a cuboidal granulosa cell during the primordial-to-primary follicle transition.

A pigment cell derived from the neural crest. The cell contains flat light-reflecting platelets, probably of guanine, in stacks called reflecting platelets or iridisomes. The color-generating components produce a silver, gold, or iridescent color.
A(n) basal cell that is cycling.
A pigment cell derived from the neural crest. Contains cartenoid pigments in structures called pterinosomes or xanthosomes. This gives an appearance ranging from a golden yellow to orange and red.
A(n) myeloid cell that is cycling.
A(n) pulmonary alveolar type 2 cell that is cycling.
A rounded cell that is usually situated next to sinusoids. secretes follicular stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).
An adipocyte of perirenal fat tissue.
An adipocyte that is part of the breast.
An endothelial cell of the umbilical vein.
A secretory cell that discharges its product without loss of cytoplasm.

An adult angioblastic cell released from the bone marrow, or from the kidney in some teleost species, capable of blood circulation and participation in angiogenesis by differentiating into blood vessel endothelial cells.

term: neuron of the ventral spinal cord
comment: A neuron of the ventral spinal cord.
A neuron of the striatum.
A peptide hormone cell that secretes prolactin.
A neuron of the substantia nigra.
An epithelial cell that is part of the conjunctiva.
A peptide hormone secreting cell pituitary that produces luteinizing hormone.
An adipocyte that is part of omentum tissue.
A cell of the intermediate pituitary that produces melanocyte stimulating hormone.
A fibroblast of skin.
Any epithelial cell that is part of some gingival epithelium.
A chromaffin cell that is part of the paraganglion.
A stromal cell of the prostate.
A chromaffin cell that is part of the paraaortic body.
A muscle cell in which the fibers are organised into sarcomeres but in which adjacent myofibrils are offset from each other, producing an oblique banding pattern.
A chromaffin cell that is part of the adrenal cortex.
Any secretory cell that is capable of some calcitonin secretion.
A chromaffin cell that is part of the adrenal gland.

A cell with extensive dendritic processes found in the B cell areas (primary follicles and germinal centers) of lymphoid tissue. They are unrelated to the dendritic cell associated with T cells. Follicular dendritic cells have Fc receptors and C3b receptors, but unlike other dendritic cells, they do not process or present antigen in a way that allows recognition by T cells. Instead, they hold antigen in the form of immune complexes on their surfaces for long periods and can present antigen to B cells during an immune response.
A stem cell that gives rise to the follicle cells that surround the oocyte in female arthropods.
A somatic stem cell that is part of the epidermis.
Any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a breast.
Any fibroblast that is part of a optic choroid.

Cells of the uterine chorion that acquire specialized structural and/or functional features that characterize chorionic trophoblasts. These cells will migrate towards the spongiotrophoblast layer and give rise to syncytiotrophoblasts of the labyrinthine layer.
Neuron that secretes the neurotransmitter galanin.
Sympathetic neurons are part of the sympathetic nervous system and are primarily adrenergic producing the neurotransmitter noradrenalin along with other neuropeptides.
Parasympathetic neurons are part of the parasympathetic nervous sysem and the cell bodies lie in the brain and sacral region of the spinal cord. The neurons are mainly cholinergic.
An adipocyte with light coloration and few mitochondria. It contains a scant ring of cytoplasm surrounding a single large lipid droplet or vacuole.
A mature astrocyte that is capable of producing cytokines.

term: mesenchymal stem cell of femoral bone marrow
comment: Any mesenchymal stem cell of the bone marrow that is part of a femur.
An immature microglial cell with a ramified morphology.
Any pericyte cell that is part of a placenta.
An epithelial cell of the parathyroid gland that is arranged in wide, irregular interconnecting columns. responsible for the synthesis and secretion of parathyroid hormone.
A mature microglial cell that has changed shape to an amoeboid morphology and is capable of cytokine production and antigen presentation.

term: skeletal muscle tissue of pectoralis major striated muscle cell
comment: Any striated muscle cell that is part of a skeletal muscle tissue of pectoralis major.
Any vein endothelial cell that is part of a hindlimb stylopod.
An acinar cell of salivary gland.
Any endodermal cell that is part of a anterior visceral endoderm.

A lactocyte that highly expresses genes associated with transcription, immune cell function, and cellular stress. A lactocyte type 1 also expresses genes involved in milk component biosynthesis (e.g., LALBA and CSNs), albeit at lower levels than a lactocyte type 2.
A paneth cell of the appendix.
Any leukocyte that is part of a spleen.

term: luminal hormone-sensing cell of mammary gland
comment: A luminal epithelial cell of the mammary gland that transduces endocrine cues to orchestrate proliferation, architectural remodeling, and differentiation of other cells in the mammary gland via paracrine signaling. This cell expresses high levels of estrogen receptors. In humans, a luminal hormone-sensing cell can be identified by high levels of EpCAM and low levels of CD49f, and in mice it can be identified by low levels of CD29 and high levels of Foxa1, CD133, and Sca1 (Ly6a).
A cell of the seminiferous tubule epithelium.
Any migratory neural crest cell that is part of a cardiac neural crest.

term: luminal adaptive secretory precursor cell of mammary gland
comment: A luminal epithelial cell of the mammary gland that can proliferate and has the potential to differentiate into a lactocyte during pregnancy. In humans, a luminal adaptive secretory precursor cell can be identified by high levels of the markers EpCAM and CD49f, and in mice it can be identified by low levels of CD29 and high levels of CD14, Kit, CD61, and Tspan8.

A cell from the thermogenic form of adipose tissue found in many species, particularly in newborns and hibernating mammals, but also in lesser amounts in adults of other mammals including humans. Brown fat is capable of rapid liberation of energy and seems to be important in the maintenance of body temperature immediately after birth and upon waking from hibernation.
An immature astrocyte.
Any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a adipose tissue.
A differentiated flat keratinocyte that is part of a nail plate. An onychocyte is firmly adherent and does not desquamate.

A cell of hematopoietic origin, typically resident in particular tissues, specialized in the uptake, processing, and transport of antigens to lymph nodes for the purpose of stimulating an immune response via T cell activation. These cells are lineage negative (CD3-negative, CD19-negative, CD34-negative, and CD56-negative).
A spore formed from bacteria in the order Actinomycetales.

A supporting cell that is part of the ovary and differentiates into a granulosa cell. A pre-granulosa cell develops from an early supporting gonadal cell by repressing testis determination, which can then proliferate to form primordial follicles.

term: epithelial cell of upper respiratory tract
comment: Any epithelial cell that is part of some upper respiratory tract epithelium.

A mature B cell that serves as an intermediate stage in the differentiation of naive B cells into a plasmablast. A preplasmablast expresses CD30 and IL-6R and lacks expression of CD20, CD23, CD38 and CD138.

term: epithelial cell of lower respiratory tract
comment: Any epithelial cell that is part of some lower respiratory tract epithelium.
A tissue-resident macrophage that is part of the uterus.
A basal cell in the respiratory tract.

A trophoblast cell that invades the maternal spiral arteries and replace the endothelial lining, remodeling the vessels and allowing for adequate blood transport into the placenta. An endovascular extravillous trophoblast cell differentiates from an extravillous trophoblast cell. In humans, this cell can be distinguished by the expression of CD56.

A trophoblast cell that invades the uterine wall to anchor the placenta to the uterus. An interstitial extravillous trophoblast cell differentiates from an extravillous trophoblast cell, becoming hyperchromatic and changing its morphology to a fibroblast-like spindle-shaped cell. In humans, this cell can be distinguished by the expression of placental-specific protein 8, which stimulates migration.

A cell capable of producing epinephrine. Epiniphrine is synthesized from norepiniphrine by the actions of the phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase enzyme, which is expressed in the adrenal glands, androgenic neurons, and in other cell types.

term: endothelial cell of central vein of liver
comment: An endothelial cell that is part of a central vein of liver.

Langerhans cell is a conventional dendritic cell that has plasma membrane part CD207. A Langerhans cell is a stellate dendritic cell of myeloid origin, that appears clear on light microscopy and has a dark-staining, indented nucleus and characteristic inclusions (Birbeck granules) in the cytoplasm. Langerhans cells are found principally in the stratum spinosum of the epidermis, but they also occur in other stratified epithelia and have been identified in the lung, lymph nodes, spleen, and thymus.
A lactocyte that highly expresses genes associated with lipid production and milk component biosynthesis.
Any fibroblast that is part of a gallbladder.
Any melanocyte of skin that is part of a skin of face.
Neuron that secretes histamine.
Any epithelial cell that is part of some pronephric nephron tubule.

term: mesenchymal stem cell of abdominal adipose tissue
comment: Any mesenchymal stem cell of adipose tissue that is part of an abdomen.

A neuroendocrine cell that secretes gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH). A GnRH neuron is born in the nasal placode during embryonic development and migrates through the nose and forebrain to the hypothalamus. This cell regulates reproduction by secreting GnRH into the pituitary portal vessels to induce the release of gonadotropins into the general circulation.

A segmented neutrophilic cell of the bone marrow reserve pool that expresses CD11b (integrin alpha-M) and high levels of CD16 (low affinity immunoglobulin gamma Fc region receptor III) on its cell surface.
Neuron found in the spiral ganglion.

A cell capable of producting norepiniphrine. Norepiniphrine is a catecholamine with multiple roles including as a hormone and a neurotransmitter. In addition, epiniphrine is synthesized from norepiniphrine by the actions of the phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase enzyme.

A respiratory stem cell found at the junction of the terminal (conductive) bronchiole and the respiratory bronchiole. This cell types gives rise to alveolar cell types and club cells in response to lung injury. This cell type expresses markers Scgb1a1 and Sftpc.
A cell type that secretes 5-Hydroxytryptamine (serotonin).

An amniotic stem cell is a mesenchymalstem cell extracted from amniotic fluid. Amniotic stem cells are able to differentiate into various tissue type such as skin, cartilage, cardiac tissue, nerves, muscle, and bone

A granule cell that has soma location in the dentate gyrus cell layer of the hippocampal formation and has an elliptical cell body and characteristic cone-shaped tree of spiny apical dendrites. The branches extend throughout the molecular layer and the distal tips of the dendritic tree end just at the hippocampal fissure or at the ventricular surface. The dentate gyrus granule cell is the principal cell type of the dentate gyrus.
Any basket cell that is part of a Ammon's horn.
Any secretory cell that is capable of some mineralocorticoid secretion.

term: dentate gyrus of hippocampal formation basket cell
comment: Any basket cell that is part of a dentate gyrus of hippocampal formation.
An epithelial cell of the anal column.
Any basket cell that is part of a neocortex.

term: nonkeratinized epithelial cell of anal column
comment: A nonkeratinized epithelial cell of the anal canal.
Any mononuclear cell that is part of a umbilical cord.
A(n) T cell that is cycling.

term: nonkeratinized epithelial cell of inferior part of anal canal
comment: A nonkeratinized cell epithleial cell of the inferior part of the anal canal.
Any goblet cell that is part of a conjunctiva.
A(n) B cell that is cycling.

term: keratinized epithelial cell of the anal canal
comment: An epithelial cell of the anal canal that is keratinized. This cell type is found towards the lower, rectal end of the anal canal.

term: hair follicle dermal papilla cell of scalp
comment: Any hair follicle dermal papilla cell that is part of a scalp.

A follicular cell of ovary that differentiates from a cuboidal granulosa cell during the secondary follicle stage. Mural granulosa cells line the inner surface of the follicle wall, surrounding the fluid-filled antral cavity. These cells produce oestrogen during the follicular phase in response to follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH), and progesterone after ovulation in response to luteinizing hormone (LH).
A cell of mesodermal origin that is closely associated with the epithelium of an imaginal disc. It is a precursor of some of the insect's adult muscles.

term: epithelial cell of esophageal gland proper
comment: An epithelial cell of the esophageal gland proper.
A(n) alveolar macrophage that is cycling.

term: epithelial cell of esophageal cardiac gland
comment: An epithelial cell of the esophageal cardiac gland that occurs both in the proximal and distal esophagus, within the lamina propia.
A(n) macrophage that is cycling.
Any secretory cell that is capable of some glucocorticoid secretion.

term: nonkeratinized cell of stratum corneum of esophageal epithelium
comment: An epithelial cell of stratum corneum of esophageal epithelium that lacks keratin.
A(n) CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell that is cycling.

term: endo-epithelial cell of tympanic part of viscerocranial mucosa
comment: An endothelial cell of viscerocranial mucosa that is part of the tympanic region of the viscerocranial mucosa.
A(n) CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell that is cycling.
A(n) monocyte that is cycling.
A precursor of the cells that form the dorsal vessel of arthropods.
A(n) gamma-delta T cell that is cycling.
An epidermal progenitor cell that arises from neuroectoderm and in turn gives rise to the epidermal sheath of ventral and cephalic regions.
A(n) natural killer cell that is cycling.
An epidermal cell that secretes chitinous cuticle from its apical side.
An epithelial fate stem cell derived form the amnion membrane.
A(n) dendritic cell that is cycling.
A type of interneuron in the retinal inner nuclear layer which carries information from the inner plexiform layer and the outer plexiform layer, using dopamine.
A type of interneuron in the retinal inner nuclear layer which carries information from the inner plexiform layer and the outer plexiform layer.
A type of interneuron in the retinal inner nuclear layer which carries information from the inner plexiform layer and the outer plexiform layer using GABA.
A neuron that releases hypocretin as a neurotransmitter.
Epithelial cell that is part of the colon epithelium.

term: stratified non keratinized epithelial stem cell

comment: Any osteoblast that is part of a femur.
A neural progenitor cell that is the daughter of a neuroblast (sensu arthopoda). The progeny of ganglion mother cells develop into neurons, glia and (occasionally) epithelial cells.
Any pyramidal cell that is part of a regional part of cerebral cortex.
A precursor of the central nervous system that gives rise to both neurons and glial cells.
Any dendritic cell that is part of a liver.

term: lung resident memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell
comment: An alpha-beta CD8 T cell that resides in the lung.
A peptide hormone secreting cell that produces adrenocorticotropin, or corticotropin.
A large, granular, liver specific natural killer cell that adheres to the endothelial cells of the hepatic sinusoid.

term: lung resident memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell
comment: An alpha-beta CD4 T cell that resides in the lung.

term: endo-epithelial cell of pharyngotympanic part of viscerocranial mucosa
comment: An endocranial viscerocranial mucosa cell that is part of viscerocranial mucosa.
Any endothelial cell that is part of a spleen.

term: mucus secreting cell of tracheobronchial tree submucosal gland
comment: A mucus secreting cell of a submucosal gland of the tracheobronchial tree.
Any endothelial cell of artery that is part of a umbilical cord.
An OFF bipolar cell that is fovea-specific and expresses FEZF1, NXPH1 and NXPH2.
Any fibroblast that is part of a spleen.
An ON bipolar cell that has large dendritic and axonal fields.
An ON bipolar cell with a small dendritic tree that forms most of the central (invaginating) elements opposite the synaptic ribbon at the cone triad.
A cell whose primary function is to protect the organism.

term: endothelial cell of high endothelial venule
comment: A venule endothelial cell that is cubodial, expresses leukocyte-specific receptors, and allows for passage of lymphocytes into bloodstream.
An epithelial cell part of respiratory tract epithelium that is a precursor of a multi-ciliated cell. This cell actively amplifies centrioles, a required step for multiciliogenesis.
A squamous shaped endothelial cell.
A macrophage that is part of the lung connective tissue (pulmonary interstitium). This cell performs tissue remodeling and contributes to barrier immunity through antigen presentation.

term: epithelial cell of stratum corneum of esophageal epithelium
comment: An epithelial cell of stratum corneum of esophageal epithelium.
An alveolar macrophage that expresses metallothionein.

term: epithelial cell of stratum spinosum of esophageal epithelium
comment: An epithelial cell of stratum spinosum of esophageal epithelium.
An alveolar macrophage that expresses CCL3.
A somatic epithelial cell of the insect egg chamber.

term: lung resident memory CD8-positive, CD103-positive, alpha-beta T cell
comment: A lung resident memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell that is CD103-positive.
A basophil cell of the anterior pituitary that produces thyroid stimulating hormone, thyrotrophin. This cell type is elongated, polygonal and lie in clusters towards the adenohypophyseal center.
Any pyramidal cell that is part of a primary motor cortex.
A lower motor neuron whose soma is located in the anterior horn. Anterior horn motor neurons project from the anterior portion of the grey matter in the spinal cord to some skeletal muscles.
An insect renal cell that filters hemolymph and is found with other pericardial nephrocytes in two rows flanking the dorsal vessel.

term: endothelial cell of venous sinus of spleen
comment: An endothelial cell that is part of the venous sinus of spleen. This endothelial cell has an elongated, spindle-shaped, flattened morphology that is parallel to long axis of sinus. This cell type rests on a basement membrane interrupted by numerous narrow slits.
Any motor neuron that is part of a brainstem.
A cell that, by division or terminal differentiation, can give rise to other cell types.
A trophoblast of placental villi. These cells fuse to form synctial trophoplast - the placental side of the interface between the placenta and maternal blood sinusoids in the decidua.
Any fibroblast that is part of a pericardium.
Any radial glial cell that is part of some spinal cord.
Any fibroblast that is part of a cardiac atrium.
A peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes vasopressin stimulating hormone
Any fibroblast that is part of a cardiac ventricle.
A peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes oxytocin stimulating hormone
Any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a female urethra.
A taste receptor cell that is part of a taste bud of a tongue.
A glandular epithelial cell of the endometrium.
Any epithelial cell that is part of a female gonad.

A respiratory epithelial cell with topographic nuclear position in between the basal and luminal cell of the airway epithelium. This non-basal, intermediate cell has limited proliferative capacity, ultrastructural features of basal cells and no defined features of the typically differentiated cellular phenotypes.
A glandular epithelial cell of the esophagus.
Any fibroblast that is part of a female gonad.

A midget ganglion cell that depolarizes in response to decreased light intensity in the center of its receptive field. The majority of input that this cell receives comes from flat midget bipolar cells.

term: glandular cell of the large intestine
comment: A glandular epithelial cell of the large intestine.
Any capillary endothelial cell that is part of a placenta.

A midget ganglion cell that depolarizes in response to increased light intensity in the center of its receptive field. The majority of input that this cell receives comes from invaginating midget bipolar cells.
A glandular epithelial cell that is part of the stomach.
Any mesenchymal stem cell that is part of a placenta.
A dendritic cell that captures antigens in a lung and migrates to a lymph node or to the spleen to activate T cells.
A material entity of anatomical origin (part of or deriving from an organism) that has as its parts a maximally connected cell compartment surrounded by a plasma membrane.

Mast cell subtype whose granules contain both the serine proteases tryptase and chymase. These cells are primarily found in connective tissue, such as the peritoneal cavity, skin, and intestinal submucosa. Their development is T-cell independent.
A myocardial endocrine cell that is part of the atrium.

term: airway submucosal gland duct ciliated cell
comment: A ciliated cell that is part of a ciliated duct of an airway submucosal gland.
A peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes bombesin stimulating hormone.
A stem cell that can give rise to multiple cell types (i.e. smooth muscle, endothelial) in the developing heart.
A cell that is adjacent to a vessel. A perivascular cell plays a crucial role in maintaining vascular function and tissue homeostasis. This cell type regulates vessel integrity and flow dynamics.
An endocrine cell that secretes juvenile hormone.
A fibrocyte of the cochlea that has specialized structural and molecular adaptions.

A bistratfied retinal ganglion cell with a small dendritic field that has dendrites in the ON and OFF sublamina of the retinal inner plexiform layer and carries blue-ON/yellow-OFF signals. This cell receives bipolar and amacrine input to both the OFF and ON dendritic tree.
A peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes cholecystokin stimulating hormone.
An otic fibrocyte that underlies the spiral prominence and is part of a mesenchymal gap junction network that regulates ionic homeostasis of the endolymph.
A parasol ganglion cell that depolarizes in response to increased light intensity in the center of its receptive field. The majority of input that this cell receives comes from DB4 bipolar cells.
A photoreceptor cell that detects visible light.
A parasol ganglion cell that depolarizes in response to decreased light intensity in the center of its receptive field. The majority of input that this cell receives comes from DB3a bipolar cells.

A secretory cell of ectodermal origin. This cell may have important functions in fatty acid and hydrocarbon metabolism and is metabolically linked to the fat body and tracheae. This cell is exclusive of arthropods.

term: luminal cell of acinus of lactiferous gland
comment: A luminal epithelial cell of mammary gland located in acinus of structure.
A neuron that releases catecholamine as a neurotransmitter.

A large binucleate cell that forms a 'garland' around the anterior end of the proventriculus (cardia) at its junction with the esophagus in both adults and larvae flies. Each cell is surrounded by a basement membrane and there are numerous micro-invaginations (lacunae) extending from the surface into the cytoplasm. At the mouth of each lacuna is a doubled filament forming a specialised filtration system (diaphragm). The filtrate is endocytosed from the lacunae.

term: luminal cell of lactiferous terminal ductal lobular unit
comment: A luminal cell of terminal ducts, i.e.e the terminal branch of a lactiferous duct which alveolar cells drain into.
Any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a prostate gland.
A cultured cell that is freshly isolated from a organismal source, or derives in culture from such a cell prior to the culture being passaged.

Mast cell subtype that contains only the serine protease trypase in its granules. These cells are primarily found in mucosal tissue, such as intestinal mucosa and alveoli. They depend upon T-cells for development of phenotype.
A luminal epithelial cell of the lactiferous duct. This cuboidal epithelial cell expresses keratin-18 and is estrogen-receptor alpha positive.
Any osteoblast that is part of a skull.
A peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes secretin stimulating hormone

Cell that is part of the migratory cranial neural crest population. Migratory cranial neural crest cells develop from premigratory cranial neural crest cells and have undergone epithelial to mesenchymal transition and delamination.

term: anterior lateral line neuromast mantle cell
comment: Any neuromast mantle cell that is part of an anterior lateral line.
An ON bipolar cell type with dendrites selectively contacting S-cones.
A cell found in the embryo before the formation of all the gem layers is complete.

term: anterior lateral line neuromast hair cell
comment: Any neuromast hair cell that is part of a anterior lateral line.
A megakaryocyte that is resident in the lung connective tissue.
Any sensory receptor cell that is a(n) neuron and is capable of some detection of stimulus involved in sensory perception.
Any basal cell of epidermis that is part of a limb.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of a bronchiole.
Any fibroblast that is derived from the neural crest.
A neuron that is part of a peripheral nervous system.

A myofibroblast that is part of an alveoli during alveolarization. The contractile force of this cell elongates the secondary crest, while producing a framework of elastin and tenascin. During the maturation of the septa, secondary crest myofibroblasts, together with matrix fibroblasts, secrete metalloproteinases and other ECM‐remodeling proteins to thin the septal tip ECM. The secondary crest myofibroblast continues producing elastin, eventually undergoing apoptosis during adulthood.
An otic fibrocyte that resides above the stria vasularis and is part of a mesenchymal gap junction network that regulates ionic homeostasis of the endolymph.
Any neuron that is part of a lateral line ganglion.
A star-shaped glial cell that is part of some retina. This cell links neurons to blood vessels and may provide structural and physiological support to optic nerve head axons.
An otic fibrocyte that is lateral to the basilar membrane and anchoris it to the lateral wall.
Any native cell that is part of a hypothalamus.

A small, narrow, peg-shaped epithelial cell with little cytoplasm that is part of oviduct epithelium. This cell is rarer than the ciliated and secretory epithelial cells of the fallopian tube epithelium and is often found intercalated between them. Peg cells are generally distributed basally along the epithelium and have been found in high concentrations at the fimbriated, distal end of the fallopian tube in humans. It may have a regenerative/stem-cell function. In humans, markers include EPCAM, CD44, and ITGA6.
An otic fibrocyte that lines the otic capsule.
A keratinocyte of the epidermis suprabasal layer. This cell may express the differentiation markers keratin 10 and keratin 1.

term: smooth muscle cell of large intestine smooth muscle longitudinal layer
comment: A(n) smooth muscle cell that is part of a(n) large intestine smooth muscle longitudinal layer.

Cell that is part of the migratory trunk neural crest population. Migratory trunk neural crest cells develop from premigratory trunk neural crest cells and have undergone epithelial to mesenchymal transition and delamination.
A photoreceptor cell that is sensitive to blue light.
A S. pombe mating type determined by the mat1-Mc and mat1-Mi on the mat1 locus.

term: mucus secreting cell of bronchus submucosal gland
comment: A mucus secreting cell of a submucosal gland of the bronchus.
A cell in vitro that is or has been maintained or propagated as part of a cell culture.
A photoreceptor cell that detects ultraviolet light.
A S. pombe cell type determined by mat1-Pc and mat1-Pi on the mat1 locus.
A myoepithelial cell that is part of a submucosal gland of the trachea.
A neuroblast derived from a neural crest cell.

term: mucus secreting cell of trachea gland
comment: A mucus secreting cell that is part of a submucosal gland of the trachea.
A CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell that cooperates with other lymphocytes via direct contact or cytokine release to initiate a variety of immune functions.
A regulatory T cell that has not encountered antigen.
Any neuron that is part of a central nervous system.
A germ cell that supports male gamete production. In some species, non-germ cells known as Sertoli cells also play a role in spermatogenesis.
A connective tissue cell of an organ found in the loose connective tissue. These are most often associated with the uterine mucosa and the ovary as well as the hematopoietic system and elsewhere.
An otic fibrocyte that underlies the stria vascularis and is part of a mesenchymal gap junction network that regulates ionic homeostasis of the endolymph.
Any glutamatergic neuron that is part of a cerebellum.
A stem cell that is the precursor of gametes.

An interneuron (also called relay neuron, association neuron or local circuit neuron) is a multipolar neuron which connects afferent neurons and efferent neurons in neural pathways. Like motor neurons, interneuron cell bodies are always located in the central nervous system (CNS).
An endothelial stalk cell is a specialized endothelial cell that follows behind the tip cell of an angiogenic sprout.
Any basket cell that is part of a cerebellum.
A photoreceptor cell that is sensitive to red light.
A multi-fate stem cell that can give rise to different retinal cell types including rod and cone cells.
A photoreceptor cell that is sensitive to green light.
A skeletal muscle cell that is part of the tongue.
Any oligodendrocyte that is part of a spinal cord.
An astrocyte of the forebrain.
A CNS neuron of the forebrain.
Any glial cell that is part of some lateral line nerve.
A mature male germ cell that develops from a spermatid.
Any cardiac muscle cell that is part of a cardiac ventricle.
A male germ cell that develops from the haploid secondary spermatocytes. Without further division, spermatids undergo structural changes and give rise to spermatozoa.
Any melanocyte of skin that is part of a skin of prepuce of penis.

An OFF calbindin-positive bipolar cell that has a large dendritic field and stratifies narrowly close to the middle of the inner plexiform layer. Its axon terminal is characterized by regularly branching and varicose processes resembling beads on a string. Most of DB3a contacts with cones are triad-associated.
A male germ cell that develops from spermatogonia. The euploid primary spermatocytes undergo meiosis and give rise to the haploid secondary spermatocytes which in turn give rise to spermatids.
Any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a brain.
An OFF diffuse bipolar cell that predominantly connects to ON parasol cells and lateral amacrine cells. This cell contains a large number of synaptic ribbons and a small axon arbor area.
A stem cell that is the precursor of male gametes.
Any pericyte cell that is part of a brain.
An OFF diffuse bipolar cell that makes synaptic contact with both L/M and S-cone photoreceptors and only minimal contact with rod photoreceptors.
A CD4-positive, CD25-positive alpha-beta regulatory T cell that has encountered antigen.
Any fibroblast that is part of a embryo.
A perichondrial fibroblast that is part of the lung.

A lymphocyte found in adipose tissue that lacks lineage markers of other lymphocytes but is capable of mediating TH2 cytokine responses. This cell type is found in fat associated lymphoid clusters, proliferates in response to IL2 and produce large amounts of TH2 cytokines such as IL5, IL6 and IL13

term: dermis microvascular lymphatic vessel endothelial cell
comment: Any dermis lymphatic vessel endothelial cell that is part of a microvascular endothelium.
A fibroblast that is part of the fibrous layer of the perichondrium. This cell is responsible for collagen fiber production.
Any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a urinary bladder.

term: airway submucosal gland duct basal cell
comment: A basal cell that is part of a duct of an airway submucosal gland.

term: airway submucosal gland collecting duct epithelial cell
comment: An epithelial cell that is part of a collecting duct of an airway submucosal gland.
A stem cell that is the precursor of female gametes.
A renal intercalated cell that secretes base and reabsorbs acid in the distal segments of the kidney tubule to maintain acid/base balance.
An OFF bipolar cell with a small dendritic tree that provides most of the triad-associated basal (flat) contacts at cone pedicles.
Female germ cell is a germ cell that supports female gamete production.
An epithelial cell of the tracheobronchial tree.
An ON diffuse bipolar cell that has a large dendritic field and large axon terminals, which show little or no overlap. This cell predominantly connects to narrow thorny ganglion cells.
An euploid male germ cell of an early stage of spermatogenesis.

term: brush cell of epithelium proper of large intestine
comment: Brush cell found in the epithelial layer of the colon.
An ON diffuse bipolar cell that predominantly connects to ON parasol cells and lateral amacrine cells.

A cell type found in the gastrointestinal and respiratory tracts that is characterized by the presence of a tuft of blunt, squat microvilli (120-140 per cell). Function of this cell type is not known.

An OFF calbindin-negative bipolar cell that has a large dendritic field and stratifies narrowly close to the middle of the inner plexiform layer. Its axon terminal is characterized by regularly branching and varicose processes resembling beads on a string. Most of DB3b contacts with cones are non-triad-associated.
A germline cell that contributes to the development of the oocyte by transferring cytoplasm directly to oocyte.
A cell that is part of a cortex of kidney.

term: posterior lateral line neuromast supporting cell
comment: Any neuromast support cell that is part of a posterior lateral line.
A female gamete where meiosis has progressed to metaphase II and is able to participate in fertilization.

term: posterior lateral line neuromast mantle cell
comment: Any neuromast mantle cell that is part of a posterior lateral line.
An undifferentiated germ cell that proliferates rapidly and gives rise to oocytes.

term: posterior lateral line neuromast hair cell
comment: Any neuromast hair cell that is part of a posterior lateral line.
A female germ cell that has entered meiosis.
An oncocyte located in the thyroid.

term: anterior lateral line neuromast supporting cell
comment: Any neuromast support cell that is part of a anterior lateral line.
A PP cell found in intestine.
An epithelial cell present in the trachea and bronchi. columnar in shape. generally lack cilia. immature forms of ciliated or secretory cells which have been formed from stem cells.
Any skin fibroblast that is part of a skin of abdomen.
Any neuron that develops from some migratory neural crest cell.
Any skin fibroblast that is part of a pedal digit skin.
Any endothelial cell of lymphatic vessel that is part of a dermis.

term: smooth muscle cell neural crest derived
comment: A smooth muscle cell derived from the neural crest.
Any neuroblast (sensu Vertebrata) that is part of some forebrain.
Any blood vessel endothelial cell that is part of a dermis.
A brush cell found in the epithelium of lobular bronchiole.
A brush cell of the epithelium in the terminal bronchiole.
Brush cell of the epithelium in the trachea.
A brush cell found in the epithelium of bronchus.

An exocrine cell characterized by loss of part of the cytoplasm during the process of secretion. The secreted substance is accumulated at the apical end and is either budded off through the plasma membrane producing secreted vesicles or dissolved in the cytoplasm that is lost during secretion.
A fast muscle fiber cell that stores energy in the form of glycogen and creatine phosphate.

term: endothelial cell of venule of lymph node
comment: A(n) endothelial cell that is part of a(n) venule of lymph node.
A cell of a platelike structure, especially a thickened plate of ectoderm in the early embryo, from which a sense organ develops.
A muscle cell with low content of myoglobin and other oxygen storing proteins. This muscle cell has a white appearance.
A cell that will develop into a neuron often after a migration phase.

A type II muscle cell that contains large amounts of myoglobin, has many mitochondria and very many blood capillaries. Type II A cells are red, have a very high capacity for generating ATP by oxidative metabolic processes, split ATP at a very rapid rate, have a fast contraction velocity and are resistant to fatigue.
Any blood vessel endothelial cell that is part of a microvascular endothelium.

A type II muscle cell that contains a low content of myoglobin, relatively few mitochondria, relatively few blood capillaries and large amounts of glycogen. Type II B fibres are white, geared to generate ATP by anaerobic metabolic processes, not able to supply skeletal muscle fibres continuously with sufficient ATP, fatigue easily, split ATP at a fast rate and have a fast contraction velocity.
Chondrocyte forming the hyaline cartilage found in the knee joint.

A stem cell from which all cells of the lymphoid and myeloid lineages develop, including blood cells and cells of the immune system. Hematopoietic stem cells lack cell markers of effector cells (lin-negative). Lin-negative is defined by lacking one or more of the following cell surface markers: CD2, CD3 epsilon, CD4, CD5 ,CD8 alpha chain, CD11b, CD14, CD19, CD20, CD56, ly6G, ter119.
Any germinal center B cell that is part of a tonsil.
Any macroglial cell that is part of a brain.
A stem cell that self-renews as well as give rise to a single mature cell type.
A slow muscle cell that contains high levels of myoglobin and oxygen storing proteins giving the cell a red appearance.
Any cell that is part of a pituitary gland.
A relatively undifferentiated cell that retains the ability to divide and proliferate throughout life to provide progenitor cells that can differentiate into specialized cells.
A slow muscle cell that has large amounts of myoglobin, stores energy as triglycerides, generates ATP by the oxidative method and is resistant to fatigue.

term: goblet cell of epithelium of lobar bronchus
comment: A(n) goblet cell that is part of a(n) epithelium of lobar bronchus.

term: spinal cord medial motor column neuron
comment: Any neuron that is part of a spinal cord medial motor column.

term: vein endothelial cell of respiratory system
comment: A(n) vein endothelial cell that is part of a(n) respiratory system.
Any interneuron that is part of a spinal cord ventral column.

term: brush cell of epithelium of lobar bronchus
comment: A(n) brush cell that is part of a(n) epithelium of lobar bronchus.
A cell that is within the developmental lineage of gametes and is able to pass along its genetic material to offspring.
Any native cell that is part of a cardiac septum.

term: endothelial cell of efferent lymphatic vessel
comment: A(n) endothelial cell that is part of a(n) efferent lymphatic vessel.
A progenitor cell committed to the erythroid lineage.
Any native cell that is part of a sebaceous gland.

term: serous secreting cell of bronchus submucosal gland
comment: A(n) serous secreting cell that is part of a(n) bronchus submucosal gland.
An intermediate muscle cell that has characteristics of both fast and slow muscle cells.
Any native cell that is part of a inner cell mass.

term: smooth muscle cell of taenia coli
comment: A(n) smooth muscle cell that is part of a(n) taenia coli.
A trophoblast that leaves the placenta and invades the endometrium and myometrium. This cell type is crucial in increasing blood flow to the fetus.

term: myoepithelial cell of bronchus submucosal gland
comment: A(n) myoepithelial cell that is part of a(n) bronchus submucosal gland.

term: immature dendritic epithelial T cell precursor
comment: A double negative thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that has as part a Vgamma3 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive. This cell-type is found in the fetal thymus with highest numbers occurring at E17-E18.

term: neuroendocrine cell of epithelium of crypt of Lieberkuhn
comment: A(n) neuroendocrine cell that is part of a(n) epithelium of crypt of Lieberkuhn.

A trophoblast found at the junction of the placenta. This cell type makes a unique fibronectin-trophouteronectin junction that helps mediate attachment of the placenta to the uterus. This cell type is also found junction of the chorion layer of the external membranes and the decidua.

term: endothelial cell of arteriole of lymph node
comment: A(n) endothelial cell that is part of a(n) arteriole of lymph node.
A cell of the transparent layer of simple cuboidal epithelium over the anterior surface of the lens. transform into lens fiber(s).

term: smooth muscle cell of large intestine smooth muscle circular layer
comment: A(n) smooth muscle cell that is part of a(n) large intestine smooth muscle circular layer.

A fully differentiated basophil, a granular leukocyte with an irregularly shaped, pale-staining nucleus that is partially constricted into two lobes, and with cytoplasm that contains coarse granules of variable size. Basophils contain vasoactive amines such as histamine and serotonin, which are released on appropriate stimulation.

A cell of the cuboidal epithelium that covers the lens. The cells of the lens epithelium regulate most of the homeostatic functions of the lens. As ions, nutrients, and liquid enter the lens from the aqueous humor, Na+/K+ ATPase pumps in the lens epithelial cells pump ions out of the lens to maintain appropriate lens osmolarity and volume, with equatorially positioned lens epithelium cells contributing most to this current. The activity of the Na+/K+ ATPases keeps water and current flowing through the lens from the poles and exiting through the equatorial regions. The cells of the lens epithelium also serve as the progenitors for new lens fibers. It constantly lays down fibers in the embryo, fetus, infant, and adult, and continues to lay down fibers for lifelong growth.

term: neuroendocrine cell of epithelium of lobar bronchus
comment: A(n) neuroendocrine cell that is part of a(n) epithelium of lobar bronchus.
A myeloblast committed to the neutrophil lineage. This cell type is GATA-1 positive, C/EBPa-positive, AML-1-positive, c-myb-positive and has low expression of PU.1 transcription factor.
A lens fiber cell that develops from primary lens fiber. located towards the center of lens. cell organelles are normally degraded or in the process of being degraded.
Any photoreceptor cell that is part of a compound eye.

A fully differentiated eosinophil, a granular leukocyte with a nucleus that usually has two lobes connected by one or more slender threads, and cytoplasm containing coarse, round granules that are uniform in size and which can be stained by the dye eosin. Cells are also differentiated from other granulocytes by a small nuclear-to-cytoplasm ratio (1:3). This cell type is CD49d-positive.
A secondary lens fiber cell that lacks a nucleus.
Any endothelial cell of artery that is part of a coronary artery.
A stem cell that can give rise to multiple lineages of cells.
Any fibroblast that is part of a periodontal ligament.

An undifferentiated neural cell that originates from the neuroectoderm and has the capacity both to perpetually self-renew without differentiating and to generate multiple central nervous system neuronal and glial cell types.
A cell located between the pinealocytes.
Any lung endothelial cell that is part of a microvascular endothelium.
A squamous cell that has keratin in the esophagus.
Any skin fibroblast that is part of a arm.
A cell comprising the transparent, biconvex body separating the posterior chamber and vitreous body, and constituting part of the refracting mechanism of the mammalian eye.
Any skin fibroblast that is part of a upper leg skin.
A myeloid progenitor cell committed to the monocyte lineage. This cell is CD11b-positive, has basophilic cytoplasm, euchromatin, and the presence of a nucleolus.
A progenitor cell committed to myeloid lineage, including the megakaryocyte and erythroid lineages.
A secondary fiber cell that contains a nucleus.

An elongating cell that rapidly obliterates the lumen of the lens vesicle. Subsequently, differentiation of this cell type at the lens equator leads to the formation of secondary fiber cells that come to overlie the primary fibers.

term: light chief cell of parathyroid gland
comment: A chief cell that is bigger than dark chief cells and has a larger and lighter nucleus and a cytoplasm with few granules.
A precursor cell with a limited number of potential fates.
A cell of the basal layer of the epithelium in the prostatic acinus.
A cell of the luminal layer of the epithelium in the prostatic acinus.

term: basal epithelial cell of prostatic duct
comment: A cell that constitutes the basal layer of epithelium in the prostatic duct.
A stem cell from which all cells of the body can form.

term: luminal epithelial cell of prostatic duct
comment: A cell that constitutes the luminal layer of epithelium of prostatic duct.
Skeletogenic cell that produces enamel, overlies the odontogenic papilla, and arises from the differentiation of a preameloblast cell.

Skeletogenic cell that is typically non-terminally differentiated, secretes an avascular, GAG rich matrix. is not buried in cartilage tissue matrix, retains the ability to divide, located adjacent to cartilage tissue (including within the perichondrium), and develops from prechondroblast (and thus prechondrogenic) cell.
An epithelial cell of the prostate.

A connective tissue cell which secretes an extracellular matrix rich in collagen and other macromolecules. Flattened and irregular in outline with branching processes. appear fusiform or spindle-shaped.
An epithelial cell of prostatic duct.

A cell that is commited to differentiating into a muscle cell. Embryonic myoblasts develop from the mesoderm. They undergo proliferation, migrate to their various sites, and then differentiate into the appropriate form of myocytes. Myoblasts also occur as transient populations of cells in muscles undergoing repair.
An epithelial cell of the prostatic acinus.
A oligopotent progenitor cell committed to the lymphoid lineage.
A progenitor cell committed to the megakaryocyte and erythroid lineages.
A primordial germ cell that is destined to become a male germ cell.
A primordial cell from which an oocyte (ovum) ultimately is developed.

A cell that is usually found in a two-dimensional sheet with a free surface. The cell has a cytoskeleton that allows for tight cell to cell contact and for cell polarity where apical part is directed towards the lumen and the basal part to the basal lamina.

A neuroepithelial glial cell, derived from a radial glial cell originating from the neuroectoderm, lines the ventricles of the brain and the central canal of the spinal cord. This cell is characterized by the presence of cilia on its apical surface, which can be motile or non-motile.
A hematopoeitic stem cell found in the blood. Normally found in very limited numbers in the peripheral circulation (less than 0.1% of all nucleated cells).
A cell that has a filiform extrusion of the cell surface.
A tissue macrophage that is in the pleural space.

A pluripotent stem cell has the ability to form cells from all three germ layers (ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm). However, unlike totipotent stem cells, they cell can not generate all the cells of the whole organism such as placenta.
A fibroblasts found in interstitial spaces in the pulmonary tract. Greater numbers of these cells are found in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis.
A cell containing at least one nucleus.
An epithelial cell that is part of a duct.

term: smooth muscle cell of sphincter of pupil
