comment: An intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in cortical layer 2/3 of the primary motor cortex.

term: L6b glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
comment: An excitatory glutamatergic neuron transcriptomically related to the CT subclass, with a soma preferentially located in the bottom of L6 of the primary motor cortex.

term: L5 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
comment: An intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in L5 of the primary motor cortex.

A specialized pericyte that actively participates in the formation of new blood vessels during angiogenesis by undergoing phenotypic changes, increasing proliferation, and interacting closely with endothelial cells.

term: L4/5 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
comment: An intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic with a soma located in upper L5 of the primary motor cortex. These cells have thin untufted apical dendrites.
An endothelial cell that lines the veins in the fetal circulatory system.
A stromal cell that is part of a bone marrow.
A hair follicle matrix region cell which synthesizes keratin and undergoes a characteristic change as it moves upward from the hair bulb to become the hair medulla cortex and hair root sheath.
An epithelial cell that is part of a umbilical artery.
A neuron that is capable of some neurotansmission by glutamate secretion.
Cell of the intestinal epithelium with a brush border made up of many parallel packed microvilli. associated with absorption, particularly of macromolecules.

An absorptive cell of the gut epithelium that endocytoses microorganisms and intact macromolecules from the gut lumen and transports them to the subepithelial space where they are presented to antigen-presenting cells and lymphocytes.
A cell present in the developing CNS. Functions as both a precursor cell and as a scaffold to support neuronal migration.
A non-terminally differentiated cell that is capable of developing into a muscle cell.

A mechanoreceptor cell of the auditory or vestibular system that is sensitive to auditory stimuli. The accessory sensory structures are arranged so that appropriate stimuli cause movement of the hair-like projections (stereocilia and kinocilia) which relay the information centrally in the nervous system.
A columnar/cuboidal epithelial cell that secretes cerebrospinal fluid.
The various hormone- or neurotransmitter-secreting cells present throughout the mucosa of the intestinal tract.
A kidney cortical cell that is part of the nephrogenic zone.
Any neuron that is capable of some detection of mechanical stimulus involved in sensory perception of touch.

term: lymphocyte of large intestine lamina propria
comment: A lymphocyte that resides in the lamina propria of the large intestine.

A cell that transports hormones from neurosecretory cells. This nerve cell is characterized by bipolar shape and endfeet that contact a basal lamina around blood vessels, and/or the pia mater or vitreous body of the eye and additionally contact the ventricular surface or sub-retinal space.

term: intestinal crypt stem cell of small intestine
comment: An intestinal stem cell that is located in the small intestine crypt of Liberkuhn. These stem cells reside at the bottom of crypts in the small intestine and are highly proliferative. They either differentiate into transit amplifying cells or self-renew to form new stem cells.
The various hormone- or neurotransmitter-secreting cells present throughout the mucosa of the stomach.

term: intestinal crypt stem cell of large intestine
comment: An intestinal stem cell that is located in the large intestine crypt of Liberkuhn. These stem cells reside at the bottom of crypts in the large intestine and are highly proliferative. They either differentiate into transit amplifying cells or self-renew to form new stem cells.

term: L6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
comment: An intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in L6 of the primary motor cortex. These cells are short untufted pyramidal cells, which could be stellate or inverted.
A follicular dendritic cell located in the Peyer's patch. These cells from a meshwork in which Peyer's patch B cells reside.

A lymphocyte that is part of a Peyer's patch. These cells have a major role in driving the immune response to antigens sampled from the intestinal lumen, and in regulating the formation of follicle-associated epithelium and M cells in Peyer's patches by converting intestitial enterocytes into M cells.
A Betz cell that synapses with lower motor neurons directly.
A progenitor cell with hepatic and biliary lineage potential, identified in mouse and human, and anatomically restricted to the ductal plate of fetal liver.

A transcriptomically distinct type of mesothelial fibroblast that is derived from the neural crest, is localized on blood vessels, and is a key component of the pia and arachnoid membranes surrounding the brain. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: Non-neuronal cells', Author Categories: 'CrossArea subclass', clusters VLMC.

term: transit amplifying cell of small intestine
comment: A rapidly proliferating population of cells that differentiate from stem cells of the intestinal crypt of the small intestine. Stem cells located in the crypts of Lieberkühn give rise to proliferating progenitor or transit amplifying cells that differentiate into the four major epithelial cell types. These include columnar absorptive cells or enterocytes, mucous secreting goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells and paneth cells.
A mesothelial cell that has undergone mesothelial-to-mesenchymal transition (MMT) to become a fibroblast cell.

A pericyte that is in an early stage of development, found in newly forming or remodeling blood vessels. An immature pericyte is characterized by it's mesenchymal stem cell-like properties and high proliferative capacity, which allows it to differentiate into various types of pericytes and contribute to the structural and functional maturation of the vasculature. Immature pericytes are stellate in new vessels and elongated with less protrusions in remodeling vessels.

A rapidly proliferating population of cells that differentiate from stem cells of the intestinal crypt of the colon. Stem cells located in the crypts of Lieberkühn give rise to proliferating progenitor or transit amplifying cells that differentiate into the four major epithelial cell types. These include columnar absorptive cells or enterocytes, mucous secreting goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells and paneth cells.
A Betz cell that syanpses with spinal interneurons.
An endothelial cell that lines an artery in the fetal circulatory system.
Transit-amplifying cells (TACs) are an undifferentiated population in transition between stem cells and differentiated cells.
A type of mouse mesothelial fibroblast that is derived from the neural crest, is localized on blood vessels, and is a key component of the pia and arachnoid membranes surrounding the brain.
A(n) neuroblast (sensu Vertebrata) that is cycling.

term: corticothalamic VAL/VM projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
comment: A corticothalamic-projecting glutamatergic neuron that is located in L6 and lower L5 of the primary motor cortex, with a pyramidal morphology and mostly untufted apical dendrites terminating in midcortical layers. CT VAL/VM (ventroanterior-ventrolateral complex/ventromedial nucleus) cells have a near tonic firing pattern and are distinguished from L6 IT neurons by a lower inter-spike interval adaptation index.
A(n) type EC enteroendocrine cell that is cycling.

A VIP GABAergic cortical interneuron with a soma found in L5. L5 VIP cells have mostly local morphology with some deep-projecting axons. They show only moderate resistance, comparable to that of sst subclass and unlike typical VIP subclass cells that tend to show high input resistance. L5 VIP cells show particularly low resting membrane potential.
A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects to the thalamus.
Any stellate neuron that has its soma located in some cerebellum.

A transcriptomically distinct cortical GABAergic neuron that expresses the vasocactive intestinal polypeptide and that has its soma located in the cerebral cortex. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: CGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea subclass', cluster Vip.

A transcriptomically distinct GABAergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that expresses Gamma-synuclein. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: CGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea subclass', clusters Sncg.
A CNS neuron of the cerebral cortex.

A transcriptomically distinct GABAergic interneuron with a soma located in a cerebral cortex and it expresses Parvalbumin. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: MGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea subclass', cluster Pvalb.
A GABAergic interneuron whose soma is located in the cerebral cortex.

A transcriptomically distinct GABAergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that expresses somatostatin (sst). The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: MGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea subclass', cluster Sst.
A VIP GABAergic cortical interneuron that expresses cck. L5/6 cck cells have soma found mainly in L5 and L6 and have large axonal arborization.

A cell specialized to detect chemical substances and relay that information centrally in the nervous system. Chemoreceptors may monitor external stimuli, as in taste and olfaction, or internal stimuli, such as the concentrations of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the blood.

A cellular receptor which mediates the sense of temperature. Thermoreceptor cells in vertebrates are mostly located under the skin. In mammals there are separate types of thermoreceptors for cold and for warmth and pain receptor cells which detect cold or heat extreme enough to cause pain.
A cell with both myofibrils and secretory granules.
A fibroblast-like cell that provides support at neuromuscular junctions in vertebrates and are localized outside the synaptic basal lamina.
Any neuronal receptor cell that is capable of some detection of mechanical stimulus involved in sensory perception of gravity.
A specialized cell involved in gustatory sensory perception.
Any neuron that is capable of some detection of chemical stimulus involved in sensory perception of smell.

An interneuron that has spider-like appearance with a small round soma, a large number (7-10) of short, smooth, or slightly beaded primary dendrites that give rise to only a few secondary branches, and a branched axon that establishes a dense axonal mesh with thin shafts.
A neuroglial cell of the peripheral nervous system inside the basal lamina of the neuromuscular junction providing chemical and physical support to the synapse.
Any interneuron that has characteristic some stellate morphology.
A cell within an epithelial cell sheet whose main function is to act as an internal or external covering for a tissue or an organism.
A cell that takes up and metabolizes substances.
A cell that stores and secretes pancreatic polypeptide hormone.
A cell whose function is determined by the generation or the reception of an electric signal.

A neuron of the human embryonic marginal zone which display, as a salient feature, radial ascending processes that contact the pial surface, and a horizontal axon plexus located in the deep marginal zone. One feature of these cells in mammals is that they express the Reelin gene.
A mesothelial cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.
A cell specialized in detecting light stimuli that are involved in visual perception.

term: intestinal crypt stem cell of appendix
comment: An intestinal crypt stem cell that is located in the vermiform appendix. These stem cells reside at the bottom of crypts in the appendix and are highly proliferative. They either differentiate into transit amplifying cells or self-renew to form new stem cells.
A transit amplifying cell that is part of a crypt of Lieberkuhn of large intestine.
A specialized cardiomyocyte that transmit signals from the AV node to the cardiac Purkinje fibers.
An enterocyte that is a part of a vermiform appendix.
A mononuclear cell that is part of a bone marrow.
A mesothelial cell that is part of the colon.
Any cell that is part of some His-Purkinje system.
A mesothelial cell that is part of the small intestine.
Any blood vessel endothelial cell that is part of some heart.

term: small intestine Peyer's patch T cell
comment: A T cell which resides in the Peyer's patch of the small intestine.
Any photoreceptor cell that is part of some camera-type eye.

A gamma motor neuron that innervates static nuclear bag fibers (bag2 fibers) and increases their firing, in response to an increase in the magnitude of change in length, and controls the static sensitivity of the stretch reflex.

term: stromal cell of lamina propria of small intestine
comment: A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the small intestine.
Any endothelial cell that is part of some heart.

A gamma motor neuron that innervates dynamic nuclear bag fibers (bag1 fibers) and enhances the sensitivities of Ia sensory neurons. They alter muscle spindle sensitivity and increases its discharge in response to velocity of muscle length (rather than just magnitude).

term: stromal cell of lamina propria of large intestine
comment: A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the large intestine.

A lamp 5 GABAergic cortical interneuron with neurogliaform morphology with a soma found in L5,6. L5,6 NGC lamp5 have deep afterhyperpolarization (AHP) but narrow action potentials (APs). Unlike other deep neurogliaform cells (which are caudal ganglionic eminence (CGE) derived), L5,6 NGC lamp5 cells are medial ganglionic eminence (MGE)-derived
An intestinal tuft cell that is a part of a vermiform appendix.

A Lamp5 GABAergic cortical interneuron that has extended axons in the surface of L1. Canopy Lamp5 cells resemble neurogliaform cells in having elongated horizontal axonal arbors largely confined to L1. but the dendritic arbors are wider and have fewer branches, while the axon is less tortuous and extends further from the soma
An intestinal enteroendocrine cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.

term: long-range projecting sst GABAergic cortical interneuron (Mmus)
comment: A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron that is both an interneuron and a projecting neuron. They are found in all layers from upper L2/3 down to the bottom of L6. They have long-range projections, some with axons fading into white matter. These cells have low rebound potential, low hyperpolarization sag, and high variability in membrane time constant.

A lamp5 GABAergic cortical interneuron with layer-adapting morphology. NGC lamp5 cells have a small round soma, short dendrites, and a wide dense axonal arbor that tends to establish a dense axonal mesh with high connection probability both to themselves and L2 pyramidal cells. NGC lamp5 cells have unique synaptic properties that distinguish them from other GABAergic interneurons, including the release of GABA to the extracellular space via volume transmission, and the ability to produce GABA-B responses in connected postsynaptic targets.
Any myoblast that develops into some cardiac muscle cell.

A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron with a soma found in L5 and possesses 'T-shaped' Martinotti morphologies with local axonal plexus in L5a and translaminar axons restricted to the uppermost part of L1. They show low-threshold spiking patterns with strong rebound firing, and inhibit the L1 apical tuft of nearby pyramidal cells.
Any glial cell that is part of some heart.
A medium spiny neuron that expresses dopamine type 1 receptors and projects to the globus pallidus internus or the substantia nigra pars reticulata.
A medium spiny neuron that expresses dopamine type 2 receptors and projects to the external globus pallidus.
A neuron that has its soma in the heart.

A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron with a soma found in lower L5 with mostly local axonal arborization but with some sparse ascending axons. L5 non-Martinotti sst cells show somatic localization and local axon plexus in L5b and L5b/6 and substantial innervation of L3 and L4, and receive thalamic input from the ventral posteromedial nucleus and specifically target L4 neurons, avoiding L5 pyramidal cells. L5 non-Martinotti sst cells tend to show a higher input resistance and seem to be less stuttering.

A supporting cell projecting inward from the basement membrane of seminiferous tubules. They surround and nourish the developing male germ cells and secrete androgen binding protein. Their tight junctions with the spermatogonia and spermatocytes provide a blood-testis barrier.
A cell whose primary function is to prevent the transport of stuff across compartments.
A type of glomus or chief cell, is sensitive to hypoxia and produce catecholamines.
A cell located in the synovial joint.
A cell that moves by its own activities.
A neuroglial cell of the peripheral nervous system which forms the insulating myelin sheaths of peripheral axons.
A precursor B cell that is AA4-positive, IgM-negative, CD19-positive, CD43-positive and HSA-positive.

term: mature dendritic epithelial T cell precursor
comment: A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that has as part a Vgamma3 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative. This cell-type is found in the fetal thymus with highest numbers occurring at E17-E18.
A resting mature B cell within the Peyer's patch that is CD19-positive, B220-positive, IgM-positive, AA4-negative, CD23-positive, CD43-negative, and CD5-negative.
A cell of the inner of the three germ layers of the embryo.
A cell of the middle germ layer of the embryo.
A cell of the outer of the three germ layers of the embryo.
A goblet cell that is located in the colon.
A macrophage that is located in the colon.

A cell with a flagellum surrounded by a collar of microvilli. The motion of the flagellum draws water past the microvilli, serving either a feeding or sensory function. Collar cells are found in multiple animals, including sponges, echinoderms, and cnidarians. They are also found outside animals in the choanoflagellates. Although collar cells are superficially similar, their cytoskeletal structure and functional biology are different in different groups of organisms.

term: lymph node mantle zone B cell
comment: A B lymphocyte that resides in the mantle zone of the lymph node germinal center. These are generally IgM and IgD positive activated B cells that form a 'corona' around the germinal center and are part of the establishment of a secondary lymphatic follicule.
A highly specialized cell type exclusive to and forming neuroepithelium of the Saccus vasculosus, covering the caudal diverticulum of the infundibular recess.
A macrophage located in the vermiform appendix.

term: L2/3/5 fan Martinotti sst GABAergic interneuron (Mmus)
comment: A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron that has "fanning-out' Martinotti morphology that is found in layer 2/3/5 of the cerebral cortex. They have local axon arbor and long ascending axons that spreads horizontally and arborizes significantly in L1.

term: stromal cell of lamina propria of vermiform appendix
comment: A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the vermiform appendix.
A zygote in a plant or an animal.
A dendritic cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.
A plasma cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.

A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron with a soma found in lower L2/3 and upper 5, L4 Sst cells have Martinotti morphology with ascending axons but denser local axons and sparser ‘fanning-out’ projections to L1. L4 sst cells have smaller membrane time constant to calb2 (L2/3/5 fan Martinotti Cell) and non-zero afterdepolarization (ADP).
A B cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.
A T cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.
A retinal ganglion cell that is depolarized by decreased illumination of their receptive field center.
A tuft cell that is a part of the colon.

term: stromal cell of lamina propria of colon
comment: A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the colon.
A cell with more than one nucleus.
A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative.
Any cell that has characteristic some binucleate.

A double negative post-natal thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that does not contain a Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive.
A cell with a single nucleus.
A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that does not contain the Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative.
A cell that lacks a nucleus.

A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative. This cell-type is found in the fetal thymus.
A thymocyte found in the fetal thymus.
A post-natal thymocyte expressing components of the gamma-delta T cell receptor. This cell type is always double-negative (i.e. CD4-negative, CD8-negative).

A double negative post-natal thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing a Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive.

A cell that is found in the periacinar space of the exocrine pancreas and in perivascular and periductal regions of the pancreas, and has long cytoplasmic processes that encircle the base of the acinus. Expresses several intermediate filament proteins including vimentin and nestin. Shares many of the characteristics of hepatatic stellate cells, but not stellate cells of the central nervous system. Upon activation, this cell type undergoes morphological and gene expression changes that make the cell suggestive of being a type of myofibroblast.
A gamma-delta receptor that expresses Vgamma1.1 but does not express Vdelta6.3 chains in the T-cell receptor.
A gamma-delta receptor that expresses Vgamma1.1-Vdelta6.3 chains in the T-cell receptor.
A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-negative thymocyte that is CD24-negative.

A mononuclear phagocyte present in variety of tissues, typically differentiated from monocytes, capable of phagocytosing a variety of extracellular particulate material, including immune complexes, microorganisms, and dead cells.
Any cell capable of ingesting particulate matter via phagocytosis.
A non-nucleated disk-shaped cell formed by extrusion from megakaryocytes, found in the blood of all mammals, and mainly involved in blood coagulation.
A red blood cell. In mammals, mature erythrocytes are biconcave disks containing hemoglobin whose function is to transport oxygen.

term: smooth muscle cell of high endothelial venule of lymph node
comment: A layer of smooth muscle cells that forms the outer layer of the high endothelial venule of lymph node and pumps to allow flow of lymph fluid carrying lymphocytes.
A macrophage that is located in the anorectum.

term: macrophage of medullary sinus of lymph node
comment: A macrophage found in the medullary sinus of the lymph node.

term: T cell of medullary sinus of lymph node
comment: A T cell found in the lymph node medullary sinus.

term: B cell of medullary sinus of lymph node
comment: A B cell found in the lymph node medullary sinus.

term: lymphocyte of small intestine lamina propria
comment: A lymphocyte that resides in the lamina propria of the small intestine. Lamina propria leukocytes and intraepithelial lymphocytes are the effector compartments of the gut mucosal immune system. Lymphocytes circulate through gut associated lymphoid tissues until recruitment by intestinal antigens. They are involved in the gut immune response.

term: intestinal crypt stem cell of colon
comment: An intestinal crypt stem cell that is located in the colon.
A beta motor neuron that innervates nuclear chain fibers.
An enteroendocrine cell that is located in the colon.
A motor neuron that innervates both intrafusal and extrafusal muscle fibers. Low abundancy. They control both muscle contraction and responsiveness of the sensory feedback from muscle spindles.
A smooth muscle cell that is located in the anorectum.

A type of intrafusal muscle fiber that has nuclei arranged in a linear row. Unlike nuclear bag fibers, the equatorial region of these fibers (in the centre of the spindle) is not expanded. These fibers are responsible for the detection of changes in muscle length. They are innervated by static gamma motor neurons and are principally associated with type II sensory fibers.
A T cell that is located in the anorectum.
A beta motor neuron that innervates the nuclear bag fibers of muscle spindles.
A B cell that is located in the anorectum.
A nuclear bag fiber that is sensitive mainly to the rate of change in muscle length.

A type of intrafusal muscle fiber that lies in the center of a muscle spindle. Nuclei are clustered centrally and give the equatorial region a swollen appearance. They are associated with associated with dynamic gamma motor neurons, and the stretching of the equatorial region of the nuclear bag fibers results in an increase in the firing rate of type Ia sensory fibers.

A VIP GABAergic cortical interneuron with bipolar morphology, with a soma found in L2/3. L2/3 bipolar VIP cells have extending axons across all layers (with preferences for layers II/III and Va) and a dendritic tree that is vertically more restricted than deeper layer VIP cells and extend fewer dendrites into the layers outside their home layer (location of soma). L2/3 bipolar VIP cells have great variability in firing patterns, though most are continuous adapting. L2/3 bipolar VIP cells are more depolarized in their resting state, had less fast rectification, and had smaller after hyperpolarization than deeper VIP cells.
A nuclear bag fiber that is sensitive only changes in muscle length but not the rate of that change.
A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects to structures not derived from telencephalon.
A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects to structures of telencephalic origins.
An epithelial cell characterized by the presence of a brush border on its apical surface, which increases the surface area for absorption.
A pluripotent cell in the yolk sac that can give rise to mesenchymal cells including erythrocytes and endothelial cells.
A T cell that expresses a T cell receptor complex and has completed T cell selection.
A lymphocyte of B lineage that is capable of B cell mediated immunity.
A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-negative thymocyte that is CD24-positive.
A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte that is CD24-positive.
A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte that is CD24-negative.
An immature or mature cell of the first erythroid lineage to arise during embryonic development.

A modified epidermal cell located in the stratum basale. They are found mostly in areas where sensory perception is acute. Merkel cells are closely associated with an expanded terminal bulb of an afferent myelinated nerve fiber.
A reticulocyte that retains the nucleus and other organelles. Found in birds, fish, amphibians and reptiles.

A stratified epithelial cell that is part of cuboidal epithelium, characterized by multiple layers of cuboidal cells forming the apical layer. This provides a protective lining for ducts in large glands, such as sweat glands.
A reticulocyte lacking a nucleus and showing a basophilic reticulum under vital staining due to the presence of ribosomes.

A stratified epithelial cell that is part of squamous epithelium, characterized by multiple layers of cells. The basal layer is directly attached to the basement membrane and the apical layer consists of flattened squamous cells. This provides a protective barrier, commonly found in areas subject to abrasion, such as the skin, oral cavity, and esophagus.
A DN2 thymocyte that is Kit-hi.
A DN2 thymocyte that is Kit-low.

A cell characteristically found lining hollow organs that are subject to great mechanical change due to contraction and distention. originally thought to represent a transition between stratified squamous and columnar epithelium.
A T cell that has not completed T cell selection.

term: plasma cell of medullary sinus of lymph node
comment: A plasma cell that is located in the medullary sinus of the lymph node.
An enterocyte that is located in the anorectum.
A goblet cell that is located in the anorectum.
A transit amplifying cell that is located in the anorectum.

A GABAergic cortical interneuron that is strongly labelled for α7 nAChRs. These cells have soma found in L1 and have multipolar dendrites with vertically descending axonal collaterals that project deep into the column, usually branching and terminating in L5A.
A paneth cell that is located in the anorectum.

term: microfold cell of epithelium proper of anorectum
comment: A microfold cell (M cell) that is part of the anorectum.
A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects axons locally rather than distantly.

term: stromal cell of anorectum lamina propria
comment: A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the anorectum.

A transcriptomically distinct GABAergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that expresses Lamp5. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: CGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea subclass', clusters Lamp5.
An enteroendocrine cell that is located in the anorectum.

A specialized type of CD4 positive T cell, the follicular helper T cell (TFH cell), that upregulates CXCR5 expression to enable its follicular localization. These specialised T cells reside in the germinal center of the lymph node.

term: intestinal crypt stem cell of anorectum
comment: An intestinal crypt stem cell that is located in the anorectum.

term: marginal zone B cell of lymph node
comment: A mature B cell located in the marginal zone of the lymph node.
A double-positive thymocyte that is CD69-positive and has begun positive selection.
Type of neuron that is a primary mechanosensory cell, with peripheral neurites innervating the skin with free nerve endings.
A pro-T cell that is lin-negative, CD25-negative, CD127-negative, CD44-positive and kit-positive.

term: CD11b-positive, CD27-positive natural killer cell, mouse
comment: A mature natural killer cell that is CD11b-positive and CD27-positive.
A double-positive, alpha-beta thymocyte that is small and not proliferating.
A double-positive thymocyte that is large (i.e. has a high forward scatter signal in flow cytometry) and is actively proliferating.
A CD4-positive, CD8-negative thymocyte that is CD24-positive and expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor.
A CD4-positive, CD8-negative thymocyte that expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor and is CD69-positive.
A CD8-positive, CD4-negative thymocyte that is CD24-positive and expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor.
A CD8-positive, CD4-negative thymocyte that expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor and is CD69-positive.
Any cell that in taxon some Eumycetozoa.
Any cell that in taxon some Eukaryota.

A double-positive thymocyte that is undergoing positive selection, has high expression of the alpha-beta T cell receptor, is CD69-positive, and is in the process of down regulating the CD4 co-receptor.

A double-positive thymocyte that is undergoing positive selection, has high expression of the alpha-beta T cell receptor, is CD69-positive, and is in the process of down regulating the CD8 co-receptor.
An unconventional T lymphocyte population within the thymic medulla that expresses both alpha/beta and gamma/delta T cell signatures.
An unconventional T lymphocyte population within the thymic medulla that is potentially a thymic resident population.

An enterocyte found in the small intestine of newborn mammals and characterized by the presence of an apical canalicular system (ACS) leading to production of large vacuoles, important for colostral macromolecule uptake. After birth, the vacuolated fetal-type enterocytes are replaced with enterocytes lacking an ACS.

term: stratified squamous epithelial cell of anal canal
comment: A stratified squamous epithelial cell that is part of the anal canal.
An intestinal tuft cell that is located in the anorectum.

A T cell located in the lymph node paracortex, where macrophages and dendritic cells present antigenic peptides to these naïve T cells, stimulating them to become activated helper T cells or cytotoxic T lymphocytes.
A thymic medullary epithelial cell that expresses typical tuft cell markers instead of classical mTEC or cTEC markers. This population has a bulbous-like structure.
A thymic medullary epithelial cell considered to be a post-AIRE cell. This group of AIRE-mTECs is heterogeneous and also includes mTECs within Hassall's Corpuscles.
A thymic medullary epithelial cell that expresses AIRE or other canonical markers of mature mTECs like Fezf2.
A thymic medullary epithelial cell considered to be a pre-AIRE mTEC population.
A thymic epithelial cell located at the corticomedullary junction.
A muscle cell that is part of the middle internodal tract.
A muscle cell that is part of the posterior internodal tract.
An epithelial cell that is part of the urethra.
Any kidney cortex vein cell that is part of some kidney arcuate vein.
A mature CD4-positive, CD8-negative alpha-beta T cell found in the thymus that is CD24-low and has high expression of the T cell receptor.
A mesothelial cell that is part of the dura mater.
Any kidney cortex vein cell that is part of some renal interlobular vein.
A mature CD8-positive, CD4-negative alpha-beta T cell found in the thymus that is CD24-low and has high expression of the T cell receptor.
A mature NK cell that is NK1.1-positive.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is NKGA2-positive.

term: fibroblast of connective tissue of prostate
comment: A fibroblast that is part of the connective tissue of prostate.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49Cl-positive.
Any kidney cortex artery cell that is part of some interlobular artery.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49H-positive.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49D-negative.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49Cl-negative.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49D-positive.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-positive.

term: CD94-negative, Ly49CI-negative natural killer cell, mouse
comment: A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-negative and Ly49Cl-negative.
A fibroblast located between thymic lobules.
A fibroblast located in the thymic capsule.
A thymic epithelial cell located within the subcapsular region of the thymus.
A thymic medullary epithelial cell that expresses neuroendocrine biomarkers.
A thymic medullary epithelial cell that expresses muscle-specific biomarkers.
An adult endothelial progenitor cell characterised in vivo by homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. They may form discrete colonies.
An epithelial cell that is part of an endometrial gland.
The human equivalent of a DN4 thymocyte.
The human equivalent of a DN3 thymocyte. these thymocytes finish the process of beta selection.
The human equivalent of a DN2 thymocyte. typically contains two phases, in the latter of which these thymocytes begin the process of beta selection.
A tuft cell located in the small intestine.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the cecum.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the colon.

term: smooth muscle fiber of transverse colon
comment: A smooth muscle cell that is part of the transverse colon.

term: smooth muscle fiber of ascending colon
comment: A smooth muscle cell that is part of the ascending colon.

term: smooth muscle cell of sigmoid colon
comment: A smooth muscle cell that is part of the sigmoid colon.

term: smooth muscle fiber of descending colon
comment: A smooth muscle cell that is part of the descending colon.
A cell that is part of some vasa recta ascending limb.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-negative.
A muscle cell that is part of the anterior internodal tract.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49H-negative.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the rectum.

term: CD94-positive Ly49CI-positive natural killer cell, mouse
comment: A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-positive and Ly49Cl-positive.

term: myocyte of atrial septal branch of anterior internodal tract
comment: A muscle cell that is part of the atrial septal branch of anterior internodal tract.

term: myocyte of atrial branch of anterior internodal tract
comment: A muscle cell that is part of the atrial branch of anterior internodal tract.
Any kidney cortex artery cell that is part of some kidney arcuate artery.

term: Cd4-negative, CD8 alpha-negative, CD11b-positive dendritic cell
comment: Cd4-negative, CD8 alpha-negative, CD11b-positive dendritic cell is a conventional dendritic cell that is CD11b-positive, CD4-negative, CD8 alpha-negative and is CD205-positive.

term: outer renal medulla vasa recta cell
comment: Any vasa recta cell that is part of some outer renal medulla vasa recta.
A CD11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-negative and CD4-positive.

term: smooth muscle cell of large intestine
comment: A smooth muscle cell that is part of the large intestine.

term: inner renal medulla vasa recta cell
comment: Any vasa recta cell that is part of some inner renal medulla vasa recta.
A CD11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-positive and CD4-positive.
A Langerhans cell that is in the epidermis and is CD45-positive, MHCII-positive, and CD11b-positive.
A specialized hair cell that has an elongated kinocilium upon which an otolith accretes. The tether cell then anchors the otolith in place.

A multi-fate stem cell that is the source of cells for growth of the mammary gland during puberty and gestation. This cell type gives rise to both the luminal and myoepithelial cell types of the gland, and have been shown to have the ability to regenerate the entire organ in mice. This cell type also plays an important role in carcinogenesis of the breast. This cell type is Lin-, CD24-positive, CD29-hi.

A progenitor cell of the central nervous system that can differentiate into oligodendrocytes or type-2 astrocytes. This cell originates from multiple structures within the developing brain including the medial ganglion eminence and the lateral ganglionic eminence. These cells migrate throughout the central nervous system and persist into adulthood where they play an important role in remyelination of injured neurons.
A pericyte cell that is part of a lung.
An adult endothelial progenitor cell characterised in vivo by homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. These cells do not form colonies.
An extravillous trophoblast that is polynuclear.

term: endothelial cell of respiratory system lymphatic vessel
comment: An endothelial cell that is part of a respiratory system lymphatic vessel.

Any cell that is part of the esophageal non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium. In humans, the esophagus, which requires flexibility to accommodate swallowing of a bolus, is covered with a non-keratinized epithelium.
An endothelial cell that is part of a uterus.

term: endothelial cell of hepatic portal vein
comment: An endothelial cell that is part of a hepatic portal vein.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of a placenta.
An endothelial cell that is part of a placenta.

A stem cell found in the interstitial compartment of the neonatal testis. it is capable of self-renewal as well as differentiation into steroidogenic cells (adult Leydig cells). Intermediate stages of development include progenitor Leydig cells and immature Leydig cells.

An adult endothelial progenitor cell that is resident of adult vasculature and capable of differentiating to regenerate endothelial cell populations. Endothelial colony forming cells are characterised in vivo by clonal proliferative status, de novo vessel formation, homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. These cells are phenotypically similar to endothelial cells.
Any secretory cell that is part of some lung.
An epithelial cell that is part of the lung epithelium. This cell is characterised by the presence of cilia on its apical surface.
A dermal dendritic cell that is langerin-positive and CD103-positive.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the duodenum.

term: kidney outer medulla peritubular capillary cell
comment: An endothelial cell that is part of the peritubular capillary of the outer renal medulla.
A dermal dendritic cell that is langerin-negative, CD103-negative, and CD11b-positive.

term: smooth muscle cell of small intestine
comment: A smooth muscle cell that is part of the small intestine.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the ileum.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the jejunum.
An endothelial cell that is part of the peritubular capillary of the renal cortex.
A cell of a filament of a fungal mycelium.
A conventional dendritic cell that expresses CD11b (ITGAM).
A CD11b-positive dendritic cell located in the serosal portion of the small intestine epithelium. This cell type is CD45-positive, MHC-II-positive, CD11c-low, CD103-negative.
Glandular cell of exocrine pancreas epithelium. Example: pancreatic acinar cell, glandular cells in pancreatic canaliculi, glandular cells in pancreatic ducts.
A myeloid suppressor cell that is Gr1-high and CD11c-negative.
A myeloid suppressor cell that is Gr1-low and CD11c-positive.
A conventional dendritic cell that is CD103-positive. This cell type is usually found in non-lymphoid tissue.
A F4/80-negative dendritic cell located in adipose tissue.
An adipose dendritic cell that is SIRPa-positive.
Any photoreceptor cell that is part of some eye.
An adipose dendritic cell that is SIRPa-negative.
A conventional thymic dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-negative.
A progenitor cell that is a tissue-resident mesenchymal cell, important for skeletal muscle regeneration, and able to differentiate into both adipocytes or fibroblasts.

term: fetal and neonatal skeletal muscle fiber
comment: A skeletal muscle fiber found at the fetal and neonatal stages. In mammalian fetuses and neonates, skeletal muscle expresses myosin heavy chain-neonatal (MyHC-neo, encoded by the MYH8 gene). This expression disappears shortly after birth and is replaced by expression of adult heavy chain myosins.

A skeletal muscle fiber found in an embryo. In mammalian embryos, skeletal muscle expresses myosin heavy chain-embryonic (MyHC-emb, encoded by the MYH3 gene), which regulates skeletal muscle development.
Gr1-high monocyte that lacks MHC-II receptor complex.
A tissue-resident macrophage located in the bone marrow. This cell type is B220-negative, CD3e-negative, Ly-6C-negative, CD115-positive, F4/80-positive.
A macrophage located in adipose tissue that is CD45-positive, CD11c-positive, and SIRPa-positive.
A peptide hormone secreting cell that produces growth hormone, somatotropin.
An adipose macrophage that does not express F4/80but is MHC-II-positive. This cell type exhibits autofluorescence under typical flow cyometry conditions.
An adipose macrophage that does not express MHC-II but is F4/80-positive.
Gr1-low non-classical monocyte that has low to intermediate expression of the MHC-II complex.
Gr1-low non-classical monocyte that has high surface expression of a MHC-II complex.
A MHC-II-negative classical monocyte located in lymphoid tissue that is F4/80-positive, CD11c-negative, and CD11b-high.
A MHC-II-negative classical monocyte located in lymphoid tissue that is F4/80-positive, CD11c-intermediate, and CD11b-high.
Gr1-high monocyte that has a MHC-II receptor complex.
Gr1-low non-classical monocyte that lacks expression of a MHC-II complex.
A cell whose primary function is to provide structural support, to provide strength and physical integrity to the organism.
An erythroid progenitor cell that is CD34-positive and is GlyA-negative.
A neuronal receptor that respond to mechanical pressure or distortion in the skin.
A proerythoblast that is CD34-negative and GlyA-negative.

A trophoblast cell that has a large volume of cytoplasm, is polyploid and is usually mononuclear but is also occasionally multi-nucleate. This cell type is important in establishing maternal physiology and remodeling of the vasculature of the placenta.

term: CD34-positive, CD38-positive megakaryocyte erythroid progenitor cell
comment: A megakaryocyte erythroid progenitor cell is CD34-positive, CD38-positive and is IL3-receptor alpha-negative and CD45RA-negative.
A thymocyte that lacks expression of CD4 and CD8.

term: Kit-positive, CD34-negative megakaryocyte erythroid progenitor cell
comment: A megakaryocyte erythroid progenitor cell that is Kit-positive and is Sca1-negative, CD34-negative, CD90-negative, IL7r-alpha-negative and Fcgr II/III-low.
A melanocyte that produces pigment within the hair follicle.

An erythroid progenitor cell is Kit-positive, Ly6A-negative, CD41-negative, CD127-negative, and CD123-negative. This cell type is also described as being lin-negative, Kit-positive, CD150-negative, CD41-negative, CD105-positive, and FcgR-negative.
A melanocyte that produces pigment in the epithelium.
A granulocyte monocyte progenitor is CD34-positive, CD38-positive, IL-3receptor-alpha-positive and is CD45RA-negative.
A melanocyte of the retina. This cell type is distinct from pigmented retinal epithelium.
A granulocyte monocyte progenitor that is Kit-positive, CD34-positive, Fc-gamma receptor II/II-positive, and is Sca-1-negative, Il7ra-negative, Cxc3r1-negative, and CD90-negative.

A melanocyte located between the epithelial marginal cell layer and the mesodermal basal cell layer within the intrastrial space. the predominant cellular component of the electrogenic machinery that generates an endocochlear potential (80-100 mV) .
A goblet cell located in the nasal epithelium.
The flattened smooth myoepithelial cells of mesodermal origin that lie just outside the basal lamina of the seminiferous tubule.
A melanocyte that produces pigment in the dermis.
Cytoplasm that exhibits a characteristic staining and color, red or pink, with Eosin stain.
Cytoplasm that exhibits molecular interaction for basic dyes under specific pH conditions.
Cytoplasm that exhibits affinity for both basic and acid stains under specific pH conditions.
Cytoplasm that exhibits a characteristic staining and color, pale-pink, with Wright-Giemsa stain.
A lineage marker-negative, CD34-positive, IL5r-alpha-positive, and Sca1-negative eosinophil progenitor cell.
A lineage marker-negative, CD34-positive, CD38-positive, IL3r-alpha-positive, IL5r-alpha-positive, and CD45RA-negative eosinophil progenitor cell.
A progenitor cell that can give rise to plasmacytoid and myeloid dendritic cells, and to monocytes and macrophages.
A basophilic erythroblast that is Lyg 76-high and is Kit-negative.
A trophoblast giant cell that is derived from ectoplacental cone and, later in gestation, the spongiotrophoblast.
A polychromatophilic erythroblast that is Lyg 76-high and is Kit-negative.
A trophoblast cell that arises in the junctional zone (basal plate) of the placenta.
A polychromatiic erythroblast that is Gly-A-positive and CD71-low.
An orthochromatophilic erythroblast that is ter119-high, CD71-low, and Kit-negative.
A lin-negative, MHC-II-negative, CD11c-positive, FLT3-positive cell with intermediate expression of SIRP-alpha.
A cell located in the heart, including both muscle and non muscle cells.

A progenitor cell that can give rise to plasmacytoid and myeloid dendritic cells, and to monocytes and macrophages. Marker for this cell is Kit-high, CD115-positive, CD135-positive, Cx3cr1-positive, and is Il7ra-negative.
A fetal and neonatal heart cell that undergoes proliferation and is not yet terminally differentiated into a binucleate or a multinucleate cardiac myocyte.
A proerythoblast that is Kit-low, Lyg76-positive, and CD71-positive.
A T cell that is located in the intestinal epithelium and is capable of a mucosal immune response.
A basophilic erythroblast that is GlyA-positive.
A trophoblast giant cell derived from the mural trophectoderm.
A supporting cell of the organ of Corti.
A specialized cell involved in auditory sensory perception.

A polarized columnar cell that covesr the lateral surface of the cochlear duct, secretes potassium ions and forms a continuous sheet in contact with the endolymph. marginal cells form extensive interdigitations with the basal and intermediate cells in the normal adult stria.
A polarized cell that is juxtaposed to fibrocytes in the underlying spiral ligament. This cell type secretes potassium ions derived from fibrocytes through gap junctions.
An erythroblast that is GlyA-positive and CD71-negative.
A reticulocyte that is Ly76-high and is Kit-negative.

term: CD34-positive, CD41-positive, CD42-negative megakaryocyte progenitor cell
comment: A megakaryocyte progenitor cell that is CD34-positive, CD41-positive, and CD42-negative.
A megakaryocyte progenitor cell that is CD34-negative, CD41-positive and CD42-positive.
A megakaryocyte cell with is CD9-positive and CD41-positive.
A cell type that can give rise to basophil and mast cells. This cell is CD34-positive, CD117-positive, CD125-positive, FceRIa-negative, and T1/ST2-negative, and expresses Gata-1, Gata-2, C/EBPa
An enucleate erythrocyte that is GlyA-positive.
An enucleate erythrocyte that is Lyg-76-high.

term: CD34-positive, CD41-positive, CD42-positive megakaryocyte progenitor cell
comment: A megakaroycotye progenitor cell that is CD34-positive, CD41-positive and CD42-positive on the cell surface.
A megakaryocyte progenitor cell that is Kit-positive, CD41-positive, CD9-positive, Sca-1-negative, IL7ralpha-negative, CD150-negative, and Fcgamma receptor II/III-low.
A reticulocyte that is GlyA-positive.
A concave nuclear shape where the nucleus is indented to more than half the distance to the farthest nuclear margin, but in no area is the chromatin condensed to a single filament.
A concave nucleus shape where the indentation is smaller than half of the distance to the farthest nuclear margin.
Heterochromatin that is arranged in a carthwheel pattern.
Any nucleus that has characteristic some alobate.
A lineage-negative, Kit-positive, CD45-positive mast cell progenitor that is Fc-epsilon RIalpha-low.
A hematopoietic progenitor that has some limited self-renewal capability. Cells are lin-negative, Kit-positive, CD34-positive, and Slamf1-positive.
A type 5 cone bipolar cell with narrowly stratified post synaptic terminals.

term: CD2-positive, CD5-positive, CD44-positive alpha-beta intraepithelial T cell
comment: Intraepithelial T cells with a memory phenotype of CD2-positive, CD5-positive, and CD44-positive.
A type of type 3 cone bipolar cell with distinctive crescent-shaped dendrites.

A CD4-positive, CXCR5-positive, CCR7-negative alpha-beta T cell located in follicles of secondary lymph nodes that is BCL6-high, ICOS-high and PD1-high, and stimulates follicular B cells to undergo class-switching and antibody production.
A horizontal cell with a large cell body, thick dendrites, and a large dendritic arbor.

term: immature NK T cell stage I
comment: A CD24-high, CD4-low, CD8-low, CD44-negative, NK1.1-negative NK T cell.
A type 5 cone bipolar cell with diffuse axonal branches.
A hematopoietic oligopotent progenitor cell that has the ability to differentiate into limited cell types but lacks lineage cell markers and self renewal capabilities.

A hematopoietic stem cell capable of rapid replenishment of myeloerythroid progenitors and limited self renewal capability. This cell is Kit-positive, Sca1-positive, CD34-positive, CD150-positive, and is Flt3-negative.
A hematopoietic stem cell with long term self renewal capability. This cell is Kit-positive, Sca1-positive, CD150-positive, CD90-low, CD34-negative and Flt3-negative.
A type of type 3 cone bipolar cell with distinctive curly dendrites.
A hematopoietic progenitor that has restricted self-renewal capability. Cell is Kit-positive, Ly6-positive, CD150-negative and Flt3-negative.
A lineage negative, Sca1-negative basophil progenitor cell that is Fc epsilon RIalpha-high.
A hematopoietic progenitor cell that is capable of developing into only one lineage of hematopoietic cells.
A bistratifed retinal amacrine cell with a small dendritic field, dendrite stratification in S1-S2, and a second dendrite stratification in S5. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.
A horizontal cell with a small cell body, thin dendrites, and small dendritic arbor.
A precursor B cell that is CD45RA-positive, CD43-positive, CD24-positive and BP-1-negative.
An amacrine cell with a small dendritic field with post-synaptic terminals in S3 and S4.
A pre-B cell precursor is CD19-low, CD22-positive , CD34-positive, CD38-positive.
A broadly stratifying amacrine cell with a small dendritic field, straight dendrites and post-synaptic terminals in S1, S2, and S3.

A precursor B cell that is CD45R-positive, CD43-positive, CD24-positive, and BP-positive. Intracellularly expression of surrogate light chain, Rag1 and Rag2, TdT, occurs while there is no expression of mu heavy chain.
An amacrine cell with a small dendritic field that has post-synaptic terminals in S1, S2, S3, and S4.

A bistratified amacrine cell with a small dendritic field. Flat bistratified amacrine cells have post-synaptic terminals both on the border of S1 and S2, and on the border of S3 and S4. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.
A hematopoietic multipotent progenitor cell that is CD34-positive, CD38-negative, CD45RA-negative, and CD90-negative.
A flag amacrine cell with post-synaptic terminals in S3, S4, and S5. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.

term: Kit-positive, integrin beta7-high basophil mast progenitor cell
comment: A basophil mast progenitor cell that is Beta-7 integrin-high, Kit-positive FcRgammaII/III-positive and Sca1-negative.
A flag amacrine cell with post-synaptic terminals in S2 and S3. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.

A pro-B cell that is CD45R/B220-positive, CD43-positive, HSA-low, BP-1-negative and Ly6c-negative. This cell type is also described as being lin-negative, AA4-positive, Kit-positive, IL7Ra-positive and CD45R-positive.
A broadly stratifying amacrine cell that has a small dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S2 and S3. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.

A pro-B cell that is CD22-positive, CD34-positive, CD38-positive and TdT-positive (has TdT activity). Pre-BCR is expressed on the cell surface. Cell is CD19-negative, CD20-negative, complement receptor type 2-negative and CD10-low. D-to-J recombination of the heavy chain occurs at this stage.
A amacrine cell with a small dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S1, S2, S3, and S4. AB diffuse-1 amacrine cells have a tent-shaped dendritic arbor and undulate dendrites.

term: immature NK T cell stage II
comment: A CD24-low, CD44-negative, NK1.1-negative NK T cell.

term: immature NK T cell stage III
comment: A CD24-low, CD44-positive, DX5-low, NK1.1-negative NK T cell.
An amacrine cell with a small, asymteric dendritic field.

term: immature NK T cell stage IV
comment: A CD24-low, CD44-positive, DX5-high, NK1.1-negative NK T cell.
A bistratified amacrine cell with a small dendritic field that has dendrite stratification in S2, and in S3 and S4.
A resident monocyte that is Gr-1 low, CD43-positive, and CX3CR1-positive.
A retinal amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S1, S2, S3, and S4. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA).
A conventional thymic dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-positive.
An amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S2, S3, and S4. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA).
A bistratified amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S1-S2, and S4.
A bistratified amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field, a flat and sparse dendritic arbor, and post-synaptic terminals at the intersections of S1 and S2, and S3 and S4.

An immature B cell that is IgM-positive, CD45R-positive, CD43-low, CD25-negative, and CD127-negative. This cell type has also been described as being AA4-positive, IgM-positive, CD19-positive, CD43-low/negative, and HSA-positive.

An amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals that stratify at S2, with a second stratification that occurs in S3 and S4. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.
An immature B cell that is CD38-negative, CD10-low, CD21-low, and CD22-high.

An amacrine cell with a flat dendritic arbor and a medium dendritic field. Starburst amacrine cells have post-synaptic terminals in S2. This cell type releases the neurotransmitters gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) and acetylcholine.

A mature B cell subset originally defined as having being CD45R-positive, IgM-positive, IgD-positive and CD43-negative. Subsequent research demonstrated being CD21-positive and CD23-negative and CD93 negative.
An amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S2 and S3. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA).
A classical monocyte that is CD14-positive, CD16-negative, CD64-positive, CD163-positive.
An amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S2, and in S3-S4.
A pre-BCR-positive precursor B cell that is CD24-high, CD25-positive, CD43-positive, CD45R-positive and BP-positive.
A pre-BCR positive B cell that is CD38-high.

A pre-B cell that is pre-BCR-negative, and the kappa- and lambda- light immunoglobulin light chain-negative, CD43-low, and is BP-1-positive, CD45R-positive and CD25-positive. This cell type is also described as being AA4-positive, IgM-negative, CD19-positive, CD43-low/negative, and HSA-positive.
A broadly stratifying amacrine cell with a small dendritic field and a complex dendritic arbor. Recurving diffuse amacrine cells have post-synaptic terminals in S2, S3, and S4.
A small pre-B cell that is CD22-positive and CD38-low.
A bistratified amacrine cell with a small dendritic field that has post-synaptic terminals in S1 and the border of S1-S2, and termination of a second arbor within the border of S2-S3 and S3.

Mostly cylindrical, resemble Type 1 in their contents and the presence of a kinocilium and stereocilium apically. much greater variation in size, some almost span the entire thickness of the sensory epithelium, while others are smaller than Type 1. receive multiple efferent nerve boutons around their bases as well as afferent endings, which are small expansions rather than chalices.
A neuron that stratifies dendrites at two and only two locations.
An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field, dendrites in S4, and post-synaptic terminals in S4.

A neuroendocrine cell found in the epithelium of the lungs and respiratory tract. This cell type is rounded or elliptical in shape, situated mainly in the basal part of the epithelium. regulates bronchial secretion, smooth muscle contraction, lobular growth, ciliary activity and chemoreception. Cell has an electron-lucent cytoplasm, contains numerous dense-cored vesicles with a clear halo between the core and the limiting membrane.

An amacrine cell with a wild dendritic field, dendrites in S3, and post-synaptic terminals in S3. Dendrites have spikes, cross over each other, and cover a larger volume than dendrties of W3-1 retinal amacrine cells.
An enteroendocrine cell that produces glucagon.
A central nervous system neuron that stratifies at one and only one location.

Specialized cardiac myocyte that is subendocardially interspersed with the regular cardiac muscle cell. They are uninucleate cylindrical cells, associated end-to-end in long rows, continue from the node to the atrioventricular bundle. relatively short compared to ordinary myocytes but are nearly twice their diameter.
An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S5. This cell type releases the neurotransmitters gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) and serotonin.

A T-helper cell that is characterized by secreting interleukin 9 and responding to helminth infections. This cell-type can derives from Th2 cells in the presence of TGF-beta and IL-4. Th2 cytokine production is surpressed.
An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field, dendrites in S1, and post-synaptic terminals in S1.

A squamous pulmonary alveolar epithelial cell that is flattened and branched. A pulmonary alveolar type 1 cell covers more than 98% of the alveolar surface. This large cell has thin (50-100 nm) cytoplasmic extensions to form the air-blood barrier essential for normal gas exchange.

A pulmonary alveolar epithelial cell that modulates the fluid surrounding the alveolar epithelium by secreting and recycling surfactants. This cell type also contributes to tissue repair and can differentiate after injury into a pulmonary alveolar type 1 cell. This cuboidal cell is thicker than squamous alveolar cells, have a rounded apical surface that projects above the level of surrounding epithelium. The free surface is covered by short microvilli.
An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field, dendrites in S3, and post-synaptic terminals in S3. Dendrites of this cell type are straight and minimally branched.

A secretory cell found in pancreatic acini that secretes digestive enzymes and mucins. This cell is a typical zymogenic cell, have a basal nucleus and basophilic cytoplasm consisting of regular arrays of granular endoplasmic reticulum with mitochondria and dense secretory granules.
An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field, dendrites in S2, and post-synaptic terminals in S1.
A melanin-containing macrophage that obtains the pigment by phagocytosis of melanosomes.

term: fibroblast of outer membrane of prostatic capsule
comment: A fibroblast that is part of the outer membrane of prostatic capsule.
An epithelial cell derived from endoderm.
An epithelial cell derived from ectoderm.
Epithelial cell derived from mesoderm or mesenchyme.
Epithelial cell found in the ducts of the pancreas. This cell type contributes to the high luminal pH.
A specialized cardiac myocyte in the sinoatrial and atrioventricular nodes. The cell is slender and fusiform confined to the nodal center, circumferentially arranged around the nodal artery.
An amicrine that has a narrow dendritic field.
Specialized cardiac myocyte which is in the internodal tract and atrioventricular node. The cell is more slender than ordinary atrial myocytes and has more myofibrils than nodal myocytes.
An amicrine that stratifies dendrites at two and only two locations.

The myoendocrine cellis a specialized myocyte localized mainly in the right and left atrial appendages, and also scattered within other areas of the atria and along the conductive system in the ventricular septum. The most conspicuous feature distinguishing myoendocrine cells from other atrial myoctyes is the presence of membane-bounded secretory granules (these granules contain precursor of cardiodilatins or atrial natriuretic polypeptides).
An amicrine that has a wide dendritic field.

Infrequent type of columnar epithelial cell. This cell is characterized by the presence of a tuft of blunt, squat microvilli (approximately 120-140/cell) on the cell surface. The microvilli contain filaments that stretch into the underlying cytoplasm. They have a distinctive pear shape with a wide base and a narrow microvillous apex. Function not known.
An amicrine that has a medium dendritic field.
A fibroblast that is part of the skin of scalp.

Bottle-shaped with narrow neck. broad, rounded basal portion where nucleus is located. stereocilia and a single kinocilium is present apically. receive nerve bouton at their base from an afferent cup-shaped (chalice or calyx) nerve ending.

term: enterocyte of epithelium of large intestine
comment: Columnar cell which populate the epithelium of large intestine and absorb water. This cell is the most numerous of the epithelial cell types in the large intestine. bear apical microvilli, contain secretory granules in their apical cytoplasm. secretion appears to be largely mucins, but is also rich in antibodies of the IgA type.
A fibroblast that is part of the breast.
Neuron of the cerebellum.

Hematopoietic cells resident in the bone marrow. Include: hematopoietic stem cells (lymphoid stem cells and myeloid stem cells) and the precursor cells for thrombocytes, erythrocytes, basophils, neutrophils, eosinophils, monocytes and lymphocytes.
A leukocyte that lacks granules.
Any nephron tubule epithelial cell that is part of some renal connecting tubule.

This is a cell found in the gastrointestinal tract of mammals and serves as a pacemaker that triggers gut contraction. ICCs mediate inputs from the enteric nervous system to smooth muscle cells and are thought to be the cells from which gastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs) arise.

A group 2 innate lymphoid cell in the mouse capable of secreting IL-13 in response to a helminth infection. This cell is lineage-negative, ICOS-positive, IL1RL1-positive, IL7Ralpha-positive, and IL17Br-positive.

term: type I cell of adrenal medulla
comment: A chromaffin cell of the adrenal medulla that produces norepinephrine.

A Boettcher cell is a polyhedral cells on the basilar membrane of the cochlea, and is located beneath Claudius cells. A Boettcher cell is considered a supporting cell for the organ of Corti, and is present only in the lower turn of the cochlea. These cells interweave with each other, and project microvilli into the intercellular space. Because of their structural specialization, a Boettcher cell is believed to play a significant role in the function of the cochlea. They demonstrate high levels of calmodulin, and may be involved in mediating Ca(2+) regulation and ion transport.

A specialized elongated ventricular ependymal cell that has processes that extend to the outer, or pial, surface of the CNS. A tanycyte is found in the adult brain, specifically in the third ventricle, cerebral aqueduct, spinal canal, and floor of the fourth ventricle. This cell type is involved in hormonal regulation, gatekeeping molecules between the bloodstream and cerebrospinal fluid, metabolic sensing, and regulating food intake.
A cardiac myocyte that is an excitable cells in the myocardium, specifically in the conducting system of heart.

A cubodial epithelial cell that is continuous with the lining of intercalated ducts that drain the acinus. This cell type secretes a high pH solution to aid in activation of zymogens, and can differentiate into endocrine and exocrine pancreatic cell types.

term: type II cell of carotid body
comment: This cell resembles a glia cell, express the glial marker S100 and act as a supporting cell to type I cell. This cell is located in a small cluster of type I and type II cells near the fork of the carotid artery.

term: type II cell of adrenal medulla
comment: A chromaffin cell of the adrenal medulla that produces epinephrine.
A distinct endothelial cell forming the walls of the capillaries within the cerebral cortex.
Hormone secreting cell located in the cortex of adrenal gland. Glandular cells in the adrenal cortex secrete mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids and androgens.
A cardiac myocyte that is connected to other cardiac myocytes by transverse intercalated discs (GO:0014704) at a regular interval.

term: type I cell of adrenal cortex
comment: A small, polyhedral, cell found in rounded groups or curved columns with deeply staining nuclei, scanty basophilic cytoplasm and a few lipid droplets. This cell in the zona glomerulosa produces mineralocorticoids.
Circulating macrophages and tissue macrophages (alveolar macrophages) of lung.
Keratinocyte from foreskin.
A cell that makes up the loose connective tissue of the ovary.
Fibroblast from foreskin.
A cell in the hilum of the ovary that produces androgens.
Chondrocyte forming the hyaline cartilage found in joints.
A specialised myocyte that lies between the sinoatrial node and the atrioventricular node and is involved in the conduction of electrical signals.
A cell of the adrenal cortex. Cell types include those that synthesize and secrete chemical derivatives (steroids) of cholesterol.
Fibroblast from muscle organ.
One of two small cells formed by the first and second meiotic division of oocytes.
A small cell formed by the first meiotic division of oocytes.
A cell found in the bone marrow. This can include fibroblasts, macrophages, adipocytes, osteoblasts, osteoclasts, endothelial cells and hematopoietic cells.
A small cell formed by the second meiotic division of oocytes. In mammals, the second polar body may fail to form unless the ovum has been penetrated by a sperm cell.
A mesangial cell located among the glomerular capillaries in a renal corpuscle.
Any kidney corpuscule cell that is part of some renal glomerulus.
Any renal intercalated cell that is part of some papillary duct.
Any renal principal cell that is part of some papillary duct.
Stromal cell that forms the internal covering of the vertebrate brain and produces ECM for this and the choroid plexus.

A specialized ependymal cell that is part of the choroid plexus epithelium, responsible for producing cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by selectively filtering and modifying blood plasma components before secreting it into the brain and spinal cord. This cell is characterized by a brush border on its apical surface, which enhances the secretion of CSF.
Supports paraganglial type 1 cell.
A neuron that releases dopamine as a neurotransmitter.
A specialized endothelial cell that senses extracellular signals and guides the directed growth of blood vessels.
Cell that provides some or all mechanical, nutritional and phagocytic support to their neighbors.

term: kidney cortex collecting duct intercalated cell
comment: Any renal intercalated cell that is part of some cortical collecting duct.

term: kidney cortex collecting duct principal cell
comment: Any renal principal cell that is part of some cortical collecting duct.

term: kidney outer medulla collecting duct intercalated cell
comment: Intercalated cell that is part of some outer medullary collecting duct. It is known in some mammalian species that this cell may contribute in the maintenance of acid/base homeostasis.

term: kidney outer medulla collecting duct principal cell
comment: Principal cell that is part of some outer medullary collecting duct. It is known in some mammalian species that this cell may express the epithelial sodium channel (ENaC).

term: kidney inner medulla collecting duct intercalated cell
comment: Any renal intercalated cell that is part of some inner medullary collecting duct.

term: kidney inner medulla collecting duct principal cell
comment: Any renal principal cell that is part of some inner medullary collecting duct.
A cell of an ommatidium that secretes lens materials.
Any epidermal cell that is part of some stratum granulosum of epidermis.

Cumulus cell is a specialized granulosa cell that surrounds and nourishes the oocyte. This cell-type surrounds the fully-grown oocyte to form a cumulus-oocyte complex (abbr. COC). The terms cumulus oophorus cells, cumulus granulosa cells, cumulus oophorous granulosa cells, granulosa-cumulus cells are used to make a distinction between this cell and the other functionally different subpopulation of granulosa cells at the wall of the Graafian follicle.
Epithelial cells derived from neural plate and neural crest.
A crystal cell that derives from the larval lymph gland.
A crystal cell that derives from the embryonic head mesoderm.
Any smooth muscle cell that is part of some kidney pelvis smooth muscle.
Any kidney epithelial cell that is part of some kidney pelvis urothelium.
Any urothelial cell that is part of some urothelium of ureter.
Any ureteral cell that is part of some adventitia of ureter.
